<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Flooded Cities Dealing With Profiteers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Officials have had to take
actions to protect markets in flood-stricken parts of China and
deal with people who have attempted to profit from price hikes or
other illegal actions.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Harbin, the capital of Heilongjiang
Province, which is still dealing with a serious flood problem, the
manager of a local company, Liu Xiaoqiang, has been detained by
the police for making and selling lifebuoys that failed to meet
industrial standards for size, material, and strength.
</P>
<P>
Officials seized 115 of the buoys and 500 that were partly
finished, but 1,080 of the inferior products had already been sold
for 45 yuan each. It cost Liu only 8 yuan each to make them.
</P>
<P>
In another case, the city's price control department
investigated a local sausage company that was reported to have
raised its prices twice since August 11 and seized 117,000 yuan it
made from the price hikes, and has ordered the company to pay a
penalty that is twice the amount of its illegal profits.
</P>
<P>
The price control department issued announcements on August 13
and August 18 about the stablization of prices of food, including
the company's sausage.
</P>
<P>
In related developments, governments of the cities of Qiqihar
and Daqing in Heilongjiang put 200 tons of rice on the market at a
low price to put a halt to price hikes of some local vendors.
</P>
<P>
On August 12, the price of rice jumped from 2.8 yuan per
kilogram to 3.6 yuan because of rumors of a grain shortage in
local markets. The price returned to normal after the government
intervened.
</P>
<P>
The price of vegetables and meat, which had gone up along with
the rice, also came down gradually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
