<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Koreans Could Tour DPRK Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 23 (Xinhua) -- A South Korean can pay 1,000 U.S.
dollars for a five-day tour of Mountain Kumgang in the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), announced Hyundai Chairman Chung
Mong-hun here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed by Hyundai Group and the DPRK
Asia-Pacific Peace Committee on developing tourist resources of
Mountain Kumgang, Hyundai is scheduled to start its maiden voyage
to Mountain Kumgang next month, which is expected to take 1,000
South Koreans to the mountain resort.
</P>
<P>
"Hyundai will begin signing up with tourists to Mountain
Kumgang this weekend or early September," said Chung, at an
airport in Seoul after returning from a visit to the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
South Korean tourists in the DPRK can speak to their relatives
in South Korea by phone via satellite lines, trunked radio system
or walkie-talkies.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai is to operate the cruise ships while the DPRK will be
responsible for issuing visas, charging fees of the tourist sites
and the running of tourist facilities according to the agreement,
said Chung.
</P>
<P>
The runing of souvenir shops, restaurants and buses in the
touring area will be operated by a joint venture enterprise to be
set up by Hyundai and the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Chung said, South Korean tourists are to
board the ship at a port in Kangwon Province at 6 in the afternoon
and arrive at Jangjon Port near Mountain Kumgang around 7 the next
morning.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as we receive the approval from Pyongyang, Hyundai
will begin building a pier in the North's southern port of
Jangjon,'' said Chung.
</P>
<P>
The Hyundai chairman added that Chung Ju-yung, his father and
the founder of the group, who entered the DPRK through Panmunjom
last June, will visit the DPRK next month at the request of the
DPRK government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
