<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Leaders Discuss Peace Plan for DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Heads of state of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) ended an emergency
summit on the crisis in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting a South African-backed peace initiative for the
DRC was discussed.
</P>
<P>
However, it was not immediately known whether the peace plan
had been endorsed by all the parties present.
</P>
<P>
A key player in the DRC crisis, Zimbabwe, earlier Sunday
refused to go back on a decision to aid DRC President Laurent
Kabila militarily.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe's spokesman said that
Mugabe would not attend the summit as regional defense ministers
had already decided in favor of military intervention.
</P>
<P>
"SADC met and took a decision through its defense ministers
and that decision is being implemented, so we cannot go back on
that decision," George Charamba told the Zimbabwe News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Charamba was referring to a SADC defense ministers' meeting
last week in Harare, Zimbabwe. However, the meeting was poorly
represented and the decision of military intervention was
considered not authentic.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, Mugabe and Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos
who also supports military intervention were notably absent at
the SADC summit called by South African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's peace plan calls for an immediate cease-fire
and the recognition of Kabila's government until a broad-based
transitional government can be formed to prepare for democratic
elections in the central African country.
</P>
<P>
The plan was discussed separately in Pretoria on Saturday
evening and Sunday morning by the presidents of Rwanda and Uganda
and a delegation of ministers sent by Kabila,
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki Sunday expressed
confidence in his country's peace efforts, according to South
African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki has been busy coordinating the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Pretoria peace talks are going well and a
cease-fire is on the cards.
</P>
<P>
However, with the absence of three key players in the crisis,
observers are highly skeptical about how far the peace talks and
the SADC summit could go.
</P>
<P>
Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu and Ugandan President
Yoweri Museveni were also present at the opening session of the
summit, as well as Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi and a
representative of the Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
Uganda, Rwanda and Kenya are not members of the SADC. Kabila
has accused Rwanda and Uganda of being behind the revolt in his
country, but the two countries immediately denied the charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
