<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Sacks Cabinet, Chernomyrdin Back as Interim Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
on Sunday sacked the entire cabinet of Sergei Kiriyenko and named
former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin as interim Prime
Minister.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released by the Kremlin, Yeltsin said he had
signed a decree dismissing the government and naming former
premier Viktor Chernomyrdin, 60, as interim prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin declared in the decree that the government of the
Russian Federation has resigned.
</P>
<P>
The decree, which took immediate effect, stipulates that "the
interim head of the government will be Viktor Stepanovitch
Chernomyrdin."
</P>
<P>
The announcement marked an extraordinary comeback for
Chernomyrdin, who was unexpectedly sacked in March to make way for
the 35-year-old Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, lower house of parliament, welcomed
Chernomyrdin's return.
</P>
<P>
The president's decision came one week after the government and
the central bank devaluated the ruble and imposed a 90-day
moratorium on repayments of foreign debts, sending stock markets
plunging to record lows.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Kiriyenko was picked by Yeltsin to head the government
after Chernomyrdin's cabinet was abruptly dismissed in March.
</P>
<P>
The Kiriyenko cabinet, over its brief life, had largely played
the role of fire-fighters as the country was rocked by railway
blockades staged by miners unpaid for months and waves of
financial crises, dashing Yeltsin's program of a "year of growth"
this year.
</P>
<P>
The government's efforts to prop up the currency and boost the
stock markets, even with over 22 billion U.S. dollars of loans
pledged from international lending agencies, succumbed to waning
investor confidence and a chronic downturn of industrial
production and lower prices of its major exports.
</P>
<P>
The announcement last Monday to raise the ceiling of exchange
corridor of the ruble from 6.3 to 9.5 rubles to the ruble was seen
as a move that erased one of the few economic achievements of
Yeltsin's presidency, a stable ruble exchange rate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
