<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Sacks Cabinet, Chernomyrdin Back as Interim Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
on Sunday sacked the entire cabinet of Sergei Kiriyenko and named
former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin as interim Prime
Minister.
</P>
<P>
The move came one week after the government and the central
bank devalued the ruble and imposed a 90-day moratorium on
repayments of foreign debts, sending stock markets plunging to
record lows.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Seleznyov, chairman of the State Duma, or lower house
of parliament, welcomed news of Kiriyenko's demise.
</P>
<P>
He said he had expected this to happen since the Kiriyenko
cabinet "is not capable of working efficiently," the Interfax news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
However, the Duma speaker was apprehensive about Yeltsin's
decision to call Chernomyrdin back as interim premier.
</P>
<P>
"This endeavor is unlikely to succeed since Kiriyenko's
government, which survived just over 100 days, continued what the
former Cabinet was doing," Seleznyov said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Duma council will tackle the issue at its Monday
session.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov said Yeltsin should consult with the Duma and the
Federation Council, or upper house of parliament, on both the
candidacy of a new prime minister and the composition of the
government.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Shokhin, leader of the Our Home is Russia faction in
the Duma, hailed Chernomyrdin's comeback.
</P>
<P>
He said Yeltsin sorted things out after returning from vacation
and took into consideration the Friday debate in the Duma over the
country's financial woes.
</P>
<P>
In the session, lawmakers passed a resolution to recommend
Yeltsin to step down voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
It also passed a motion expressing unsatisfaction over the
Kiriyenko cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Shokhin told Interfax that Kiriyenko, central bank governor
Sergei Dubinin and presidential envoy for negotiations with
international lending agencies Anatoly Chubais failed to reveal
the actual situation in full to Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov criticized the move, saying
Yeltsin should have consulted with parliament in advance.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Kiriyenko was picked by Yeltsin to head the government
after Chernomyrdin's cabinet was abruptly dismissed in March.
</P>
<P>
The Kiriyenko cabinet, over its brief life, had largely played
the role of fire-fighters as the country was rocked by railway
blockades staged by miners unpaid for months and waves of
financial crises, dashing Yeltsin's program of a "year of growth"
this year.
</P>
<P>
The government's efforts to prop up the currency and boost the
stock markets, even with over 22 billion U.S. dollars of loans
pledged from international lending agencies, succumbed to waning
investor confidence and a chronic downturn of industrial
production and lower prices of its major exports.
</P>
<P>
The announcement last Monday to raise the ceiling of exchange
corridor of the ruble from 6.3 to 9.5 rubles was seen as a move
that erased one of the few economic achievements of Yeltsin's
presidency, a stable ruble exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency reported that Kiriyenko, now
ex-premier, was still saying in his office in the Government House
building "doing the routine job", Kiriyenko's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin is not expected in the Government House on Sunday,
Kiriyenko's spokesman Konstantin Viotsekhovich said.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear whether Kiriyenko knew in advance of his
ouster.  
</P>
