<HEADLINE> AL Stresses Egypt-France Idea on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) said Sunday
the Egyptian-French idea on holding an international conference to
save the Mideast peace process is a viable alternative in the
event the American proposal fizzles.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Saudi Al Madina newspaper, the AL Assistant
Secretary General for Political Affairs Mohamad Zakaria said
Russia, China and Japan in addition to the European Union and some
Arab countries are expected to attend the conference, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The conference, Zakaria said, is aimed at "activating the
Madrid conference terms of reference and piling pressure on Israel
to honor such terms and implement the relevant agreements."
</P>
<P>
Egypt is working with France on a joint initiative on convening
such a conference. Parties concerned with the peace process will
be invited to the conference while countries directly involved in
it will not attend at the initial stage.
</P>
<P>
The conference is aimed at reigniting the peace-making spirit,
as frustrations run high over months of Israeli resistance to the
U.S. initiative calling for a further 13.1 percent Israeli troop
withdrawal from the West Bank in return for Palestinian security
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
The AL official noted that the U.S. is "making a retreat" as
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright shies away from direct
mediation between the Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks were frozen over Israel's
settlement expansions in Arab East Jerusalem and long delays in
military redeployment. Recent direct contacts between the two
sides fail to make a breakthrough. 
</P>
</TEXT>
