<HEADLINE> Iran's President Criticizes U.S. Missile Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- President Mohammad Khatami Sunday
criticized the U.S. for its recent missile attacks on alleged
terrorist-related facilities in Sudan and Afghanistan, stressing
that differences should be solved through common sense and logics.
</P>
<P>
Meeting visiting French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine,
Khatami said Washington's hasty move is a blatant violation of
international law, and its attack on a pharmaceutical plant in
Sudan is against the internationally-recognized norms.
</P>
<P>
What has been raised by the U.S. should have been raised at an
international tribunal, so that if someone is found guilty, the
whole world would deal with him, the official news agency IRNA
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
He termed as human tragedies the August 7 bombings at
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania which caused last Thursday's
U.S. missile attacks, and said anti-terrorism campaign needs a
global will.
</P>
<P>
Terrorism, which means resorting to force to solve problems, is
the century's most ominous phenomenon, he said, adding that Iran
has been a target of terrorism for the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Calling the current century an era of clashes, pressure,
colonialism, terror and hatred, Khatami expressed hopes that the
upcoming century would be an era of dialog, peace, cooperation and
tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he hoped that Vedrine's visit to Iran would open a
new chapter in bilateral relations for the betterment of universal
peace.
</P>
<P>
Touching on the Palestinian issue, Khatami said that Paris'
stance towards the Mideast peace process is more rational than
that of other western countries.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine, who arrived here Friday night and handed a message of
French President Jacques Chirac to Khatami, termed as positive the
talks he had with the Iranian officials during his stay here and
said that "all your remarks on dialog among civilizations are
eagerly followed up in France," IRNA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
