<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: German Parties Kick Off Election Campaigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Major German political parties
kicked off the so-call "hot phase" of their election campaigns
over the weekend to make the final efforts to woo public support
with only 35 days left to the country's general elections on
September 27.
</P>
<P>
"The upcoming elections will decide in which direction Germany
will go in the next century," German Chancellor Helmut Kohl told a
mass rally of about 18,000 supporters in western German city of
Dortmund on Sunday, which marked the formal start of the election
campaigns of his Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party.
</P>
<P>
Having been German chancellor since 1982, Kohl, 68, is facing a
serious challenge this time from the main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD) and its much younger and pragmatic-minded
chancellor candidate Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Plagued by near post-war record high unemployment in the
country, Kohl's party has been trailing the SPD in opinion polls
over the past one year, though recent polls indicated that the
race has tightened with the election day approaching.
</P>
<P>
"We can win, we want to win and we will win!" Kohl told his
supporters at the Dortmund rally, apparently pinning his hope on
about a quarter of German voters who have not yet made up their
mind which party they will vote for.
</P>
<P>
A number of Kohl's allies, including his designated political
heir Wolfgang Schaeuble and German Finance Minister Theo Waigel,
who is also leader of CDU's Bavarian sister party, the Christian
Social Union, also addressed the rally and spoke highly of Kohl's
historic contributions to the European integration and the German
reunification.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that Kohl was the only German politician who
commands the international reputation and the political vision to
lead Germany to face challenges in an era of globalization.
</P>
<P>
One day ahead of the CDU, the SPD also launched its election
campaigns on Saturday with a tour through three major German
cities -- Berlin, Munich and Bonn.
</P>
<P>
"We can and will win on September 27 because we have the better
program and we have the better people," Schroeder told some 5,000
supporters in a speech in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder, the 54-year-old premier of the western German Lower
Saxony state, has been viewed as a political new face who embodies
many Germans' desire for a change after 16 years of conservative
rule.
</P>
<P>
Copying the successful strategies of U.S. President Bill
Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair, Schroeder is trying
to steer his traditionally leftist party towards the so-call
political "new center" by advocating free-market solutions to
Germany's social problems instead of SPD's traditional
big-spending and big-government ideologies.
</P>
<P>
So far, Schroeder's strategy appears to be working, with
opinion polls showing his party running up to 10 percentage points
ahead of Kohl's CDU earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
However, as Germany's economic recovery taking roots and
unemployment going down, many polls said that Kohl had managed to
narrow the gap to about three to five percent at the moment.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that a decisive factor would be the performance
of the smaller parties, namely the Free Democratic Party (FDP),
which is the junior partner in Kohl's center-right ruling
coalition, and the ecologist Greens party, which is hoping to form
a leftist alliance with the SPD in September.
</P>
<P>
But the FDP is still struggling to win over five percent of the
vote which is necessary under German election law to be seated in
the federal parliament. Without FDP's vote, Kohl would not have
won the four general elections over the past 16 years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Greens, which has emerged as the third largest
party in Germany in the past decade, has still to soften some of
their radical environmental and international policy demand in
order to make a possible the SPD-Greens coalition more workable,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Given the current circumstances, there is a growing speculation
that the two biggest parties, the CDU and SPD, might form a
so-called "grand coalition" after the September election.
</P>
<P>
While Schroeder has indicated he would be willing to lead such
a coalition, Kohl has repeatedly rejected the idea so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
