<HEADLINE> Tuberculosis Cases Reach 255,000 in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria recorded about 255,000
cases of epidemic tuberculosis in 1996, accounting for 3.5
percent of the global total, Sunday Times reported.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian newspaper quoted a report released recently by
the World Health Organization as saying that Nigeria is the number
five among 22 world countries with the growing epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Akinola Owokoniran of the Lagos General
Hospital as saying that the level of TB infection in the west
African country is estimated at a proportion of 1,000 male and
800 female per 100,000 persons.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has instituted a National Tuberculosis and Leprosy
Control program and made the treatment of tuberculosis free last
November.
</P>
<P>
However,the program has been fraught with ignorance of
government officials on the dimensions and costs of the epidemic
and the urgency of controlling it, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization blamed in the report the growing
cases of tuberculosis in Nigeria and 21 other countries on the
lack of political will at the national level to develop and
sustain effective curative programs.
</P>
<P>
Owokoniran said in the interview that the rate of infection
has been on the increase because of poverty. Even with the
decision by the Federal government to provide all the drugs
virtually free, victims can still not affort to eat good food,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Donor countries including China, Japan and Germany are
assisting some of the 36 states in the country to combat the
spidemic disease of tuberculosis, said the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
