<HEADLINE> Profile: Chernomyrdin Stages Comeback in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Viktor Chernomyrdin came back to
the Russian government Sunday, this time as interim prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
The 60-year-old technocrat, seen as a survivor in Moscow's
volatile politics, staged his comeback about five months after his
cabinet was abruptly sacked by President Boris Yeltsin in March.
</P>
<P>
His hands will be full as the country struggles to stave off
its most serious financial crisis in the wake of an effective
devaluation of the ruble.
</P>
<P>
The Kiriyenko government and the central bank last Monday
raised the ceiling of the ruble's exchange corridor from 6.3 to
9.5 rubles to the U.S. dollar and imposed a 90-day moratorium on
repayments of foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin returned to Moscow immediately after the
devaluation announcement, cutting short his vacation in the resort
of Sochi.
</P>
<P>
He held a flurry of meetings with political players of the
country, including State Duma leader Gennady Seleznyov, Communist
Party leader Gennady Zyuganov, former presidential security
advisor Alexander Lebed, prompting media speculations over his
return to government.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin held positions in the gas and oil industries in
the former Soviet Union and served as minister of the gas industry
from 1985 to 1989 under former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed prime minister by Yeltsin in 1992, a position
he held until March 27 this year when Yeltsin, saying a new team
was needed to ensure progress on economic reforms, fired him in a
surprise announcement that also ousted the majority of the
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said then that there was "no need to panic," and
Yeltsin said he wanted Chernomyrdin to focus on preparations for
the 2000 presidential race, but stopped short of advocating him as
his preferred successor.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin graduated from the Kuibyshev Polytechnical
Institute in 1966 and the Economics Department of the All-Union
Polytechnical Institute of Postal Tuition in 1972 as an
engineer-technologist and an engineer-economist.
</P>
<P>
He has been leader of the Our Home is Russia political movement
since 1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
