<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Rises in Nigerian Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Foreign portfolio investment in
the Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE) has hit a record high of 9.5
million U.S. Dollars in the first half of 1998, a 64 percent up
from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The increased investment was a mark of confidence of ratable
earnings in Nigeria's investment horizon, the official News
Agency of Nigeria (NAN) Sunday quoted Achibong Achibong, African
financial analyst of the Japan-based Sito Securities, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Achibong said that with the collapse of the Asian stock
market, foreign investors are focusing more on African emerging
markets, especially on Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"Contemporary statistics indicate that foreign investors have
gone beyond political logjam in accessing the investment
potential of Nigeria", he said.
</P>
<P>
The International Finance Corporation under the World Bank in
its recently-released 1997 rankings, rated the Nigerian market as
the second best in dividend yields out of 39 stock markets
assessed globally.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Razaq Oladejo, Assistant Director-General of the NSE,
said recently that many corporate concerns participated actively
in the Nigerian economy through rights issues acquired in local
companies.
</P>
<P>
Noting that a strong inflow of foreign capital would help
moderate the effect of liquidity squeeze among domestic
investors, Oladejo regretted political uncertainties and slow
progress in privatization are preventing more foreign investment
in Nigeria. 
</P>
