<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 500 Congo (K) Refugees Flee Into Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- More than 500 refugees
from the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) have entered the
Kigoma Region in west Tanzania to escape the intensifying wars in
the country, a Tanzanian official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Kigoma Regional Commissioner Ukiwaona Ditopile Mzuzuri told
local media that the number of the DRC refugees fleeing into the
region, on the shore of the Lake Tanganyika, has reached 557 by
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mzuzuri said the region received an influx of 180 refugees
from the DRC Friday and seven on the following day.
</P>
<P>
The displaced will be billeted at a new camp in Nyarugusu
Camp, Kasulu District in the region, officials said. The
refugees had mainly come from the eastern Congolese towns of
Uvira and Baraka.
</P>
<P>
The flow of Congolese refugees, however, had been slower than
that of Burundi, whose number had reached 1,058 by Saturday, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Burundian refugees had fled fighting in the
southern provinces of Rutana, Bururi and Makamba in the country.
</P>
<P>
At least 150,000 people, the majority civilians, have been
killed in Burundi since 1993, when the country's first popularly
elected president, a Hutu, was assassinated by Tutsi troops,
sparking a civil war between Hutu rebels and the Tutsi-dominated
army.
</P>
<P>
The Burundian refugees are kept at Nduta camp in the Kibondo
District of the region.
</P>
<P>
The regional chief said in collaboration with the UNHCR, the
region had the capacity of receiving up to 50,000 new refugees.
</P>
<P>
"We are in a position to cater for up to 50,000 new refugees
in terms of food, tents and other important services," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ditopile said repatriation of refugees from the DRC was
suspended on August 6 in accordance with international laws, due
to the eruption of war in their country. The rebels troops led by
Prof. Ernest Wamba Dia Wamba want to topple the government of
President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
He said before the suspension of the repatriation exercise,
most of the DRC refugees were eager to go back home, and the
vessels ferrying them back across the Lake Tanganyika were always
full, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
