<HEADLINE> Saddam Meets Indian Parliament Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
on Sunday received visiting Indian Parliament Speaker Sheri
Balalogi, and discussed with him regional and international issues
of common concern.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) said that during the meeting,
Balalogi praised the firm bilateral relations between Iraq and
India, and expressed India's deep concern over the continuation of
sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Balalogi said the Indian government and people would support
the Iraqi people in their legitimate demands for lifting of the
sanctions, and India would work for this end.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed crippling sanctions against Iraq after its
invasion of neighboring Kuwait in 1990. The sanctions can only be
removed upon Iraq's elimination of all weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Indian speaker, who arrived here Saturday, stressed that
India was ready to cooperate with Iraq through exchanging visits
by officials of the two countries and coordinating stand to serve
the interests of both peoples.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to reporters on Sunday, the Indian speaker
indicated that meetings of the Indo-Iraqi joint committee would
begin next week, to be attended by ministers concerned from both
countries.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz on Saturday met with
Balalogi and his delegation, and briefed them on the latest
developments in the relations between Iraq and the U.N. Special
Commission for disarming Iraq (UNSCOM).
</P>
<P>
The two sides discussed means of further developing bilateral
cooperation and bringing friendship relations back to
pre-sanctions levels in the interests of peoples of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
On August 5, the Iraqi government suspended cooperation with
UNSCOM and the International Atomic Energy Agency in weapons
inspections, complaining that UNSCOM is pro-U.S. and attempting to
prolong sanctions against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vedrine: Iran, France Differ on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Visiting French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine said here on Sunday that Iran and France have
different views over the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference before concluding his first
visit to Tehran, Vedrine said the Iranians were opposed to the
Middle East peace process from the beginning, but France regarded
the peace process positive.
</P>
<P>
The Iranians claimed that they opposed the process because it
was wrongly founded, but they stressed that they had done nothing
to stop the peace process at the same time, said Vedrine.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said that Iranian officials told him the latest events
proved that Iran's position toward the peace process was right.
</P>
<P>
"We told them that the reason they doubted the Middle East
peace process was something else, our position toward the peace
process is positive," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We prefer an incomplete peace process to ignoring peace
talks," he added.
</P>
<P>
Answering a Xinhua question about his talks with Iranian
officials over the latest development in Afghanistan, Vedrine said
that Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi expressed concern
about developments there and "we also voiced France's concern
about the country."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian officials are worried about the events in
Afghanistan and have decided to positively influence the process,
and they believe that the Afghan crisis can only be solved
politically rather than militarily, he said.
</P>
<P>
Many French citizens have been to Afghanistan to deliver
humanitarian assistance, and France believes peace would be
restored in Afghanistan when the neighboring states come to terms
even at the minimum, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Paris-Tehran relations, the foreign minister said
that he submitted the message of President Jacques Chirac to
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami and invited him to visit France.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents will make coordinations for the visit and
Kharrazi will visit France later this year or early next year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Upon his departure Sunday afternoon, Vedrine told reporters
that time has come to resume an important, wide-scale talks with
Iran.
</P>
<P>
He expressed satisfaction with the outcome of his talks with
Iranian officials. The two sides are interested in holding
constructive talks with each other in all fields, Vedrine said.
</P>
<P>
He said that more high-level political talks and contacts and
expansion of Tehran-Paris economic cooperation are among practical
ways to expand bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He promised that the French government would further encourage
its big and medium-sized companies to invest in Iran. He called on
Iran to offer more facilities to French companies in this field.
</P>
<P>
As a member of the U.N. Security Council and as an important
country in Europe, France is willing to exchange views with Iran
on international crises, Vedrine said.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine arrived here Friday night on an official visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
