<HEADLINE> Italian Olympic Head Says No Doping in Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Mario Pescante, president of
Italy's Olympic Committee (CONI), said Monday that he believed
top soccer players of Serie A never use illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sure the word 'doping' doesn't exist in soccer," Pescante
said after a two-hour meeting with Raffaele Guariniello, the
prosecutor for the city of Turin.
</P>
<P>
Guariniello is in charge of investigation of alleged
performance-enhancing substances taken by top players in Italy's
first-division soccer league.
</P>
<P>
Pescante said Italian Olympic Committee officials did not hide
evidence that would prove the use of doping substances by Serie A
players.
</P>
<P>
A top doping investigator from CONI, Ugo Longo, is set to
visit London over the weekend to question Chelsea's Italian stars
over drug allegation. 
