<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT, August 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA -- Angolan army has been on alert at its border with the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), with fighter planes in some
airports on stand-by order to prevent the flames of war from
spreading to its own territory.
</P>
<P>
The country's military sources said Angolan army has made
reinforcement especially in the enclave province of Cabinda, which
is bordering the Congo Province in southwest DRC where the
fighting is extremely tense. (Angola-Alert)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Philippine senior military officials reaffirmed here
Monday their unswerving loyalty to President Joseph Estrada,
finally putting to rest rumors of a coup plot against the Estrada
administration.
</P>
<P>
The officials, led by armed forces Chief of Staff Joselin
Nazareno, said they will remain staunch defenders of the
Constitution and will always support the President and Defense
Secretary Orlando Mercado. (Philippines-Military)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- Algeria Monday denied a report that it is
developing a nuclear program which will allow it to produce
military grade plutonium.
</P>
<P>
Algerian Foreign Ministry spokesman Abdelzziz Sebaa said that
the "allegations" by Spanish newspaper El Pais, which quoted
Spanish intelligence sources that Algiers was developing such a
nuclear program, were "unhealthy and sensational".
(Algeria-Nuclear Program-Denial)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The Pakistani government Monday categorically
rejected allegations in the local media suggesting that Pakistan
had been consulted by the United States on its missile attacks
against alleged terrorist targets in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
These reports are "completely unfounded," a Foreign Ministry
spokesman said in a press release issued Monday afternoon.
(Pakistan-US Attack)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi Monday
voiced Tehran's displeasure towards Islamabad's "unsatisfactory"
effort to release Iranian diplomats captured by the Afghan Taliban
militia.
</P>
<P>
"The work of Pakistan concerning the fate of kidnaped Iranian
diplomats were not worthy of being explained," Kharrazi told
visiting Pakistani Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Siddique
Khan Kanju, the official news agency IRNA reported.
(Iran-Pakistan-Diplomats)
</P>
<P>
-- --
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The labor and management of Hyundai Motor Co. have
reached an agreement on layoffs, ending a prolonged labor dispute
at the nation's largest auto maker.
</P>
<P>
The accord came after both sides agreed on the number and terms
of layoffs in talks mediated by the government.
(SKorea-Hyundai-Labor Dispute) 
</P>
</TEXT>
