<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK New Airport Resumes Full Air Cargo Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's main air cargo
handler, Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals Limited (HACTL), Monday
resumed full operation of its facility at the new airport.
</P>
<P>
HACTL's Super Terminal One at Chek Lap Kok started from Monday
to handle all inbound and outbound air cargoes, estimated at
around 4,000 tons daily.
</P>
<P>
The Super Terminal One broke down shortly after the opening of
the new airport in early July, forcing the air cargo operator to
divert part of its cargoes to Terminal Two at the old Kai Tak
Airport for processing.
</P>
<P>
HACTL carried out a four-phase scheme over the past month to
resume its handling capacity step by step.
</P>
<P>
Now both passenger and air cargo services at Chek Lap Kok
returned to normal, according to the Airport Authority (AA), which
oversees the running of the new airport.
</P>
<P>
Sources from AA said that three quarters of flights were
leaving on time or within 15 minutes of schedule. Almost all
arriving passengers were clearing immigration within 15 minutes,
and the average waiting time for their baggage was 11 minutes.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the AA said: "The figures show that the new Hong
Kong International Airport is achieving levels of efficiency."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
