</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Victims Become Major Concern In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Zhou Fang
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A common topic in city streets,
in offices, in dining halls or in villages of China these days is
where the flood crest is now, in Shashi, Wuhan, Jiujiang, or
Anqing?
</P>
<P>
While the Yangtze, Nen and Songhua rivers' floodwaters have
passed or about to pass, the government, the media, and ordinary
people are expressing concern about the tens of millions of people
left stranded, living out in the open or in make-shift huts, and
grieving over the loss of their homes and deaths of loved ones.
</P>
<P>
The central government has repeatedly asked local officials to
take greater care of these people, and the top leaders have made
donations themselves for the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
For the past few days, charity drives have been held in the
cities of Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou to raise money for the
flood victims. The Ministry of Civil Affairs and its outlets have
received donations worth more than 1.7 billion yuan, and
manufacturers of life jackets, bottled drinking water, medicines,
and fast food have been asked to work overtime to meet the needs
of flood victims.
</P>
<P>
The central and local governments have taken steps to guarantee
the distribution of relief goods and funds. In Hubei Province,
local authorities ordered the firing of some officials who
embezzled 2,000 yuan or more in relief money.
</P>
<P>
In the city of Jiujiang in Jiangxi Province, the local
government has said it will act as guarantor for flood victims in
borrowing rice from state-run grain mills or shops.
</P>
<P>
To prevent the out-break of epidemics, nearly 20,000 medical
teams with 130,000 people have been sent to provide check-ups,
distribute medicines, and oversee hygiene in flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
Local governments are stiffening price controls on daily
necessities, and a number of people who have attempted to make an
illegal profit from price-hikes have been punished.
</P>
<P>
The Public Security Ministry has issued orders to crack down on
criminal activities like theft, robbery and fraud in the flood
areas. According to official reports, some people have tried to
get honest people to make donations in false charity boxes that
these malefactors placed on streets.
</P>
<P>
Only civil affairs departments, official charitable
organizations, and Red Cross offices have the right to accept
donations, and police have been ordered to keep an eye open for
fake fund raisers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
