<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke082475 -Indonesian Special Force Chief Cleared out of Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Armed Forces (ABRI)
Commander Gen. Wiranto said Monday he had decided to terminate the
military career of Lt. Gen. Prabowo Subianto, former president
Soeharto's son-in-law and a former commander of the Army's elite
special forces unit -- Kompassus.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto also said two other senior Kompassus officers, Maj.
Gen. Muchdi and Col. Gen. Chariawan, would be relieved from their
structural positions and duties in the military.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto said he had taken the decision after receiving and
considering the recommendations made by an Officers' Honor Council
(DKP) that had examined the three about their involvement in the
abductions of Indonesian students and political activists.
</P>
<P>
When asked what "terminating of Prabowo's military career
meant," Wiranto said it means he will become a civilian and no
longer hold any structural military position. In other words, he
is put on retirement, he added.
</P>
<P>
The ABRI chief also said a military court trial for Prabowo and
the two others was possible if statements made by 10 lower-ranking
Kompassus officers currently also facing court trial in the same
cases produced clues that the three had committed criminal acts.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo commanded Kompassus for more than two years before he
was appointed commander of the Army Strategic Reserves Command
(Kostrad) last March.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo was removed from his Kostrad post one day after
Soeharto announced his resignation from the presidency on May 21.
</P>
<P>
Prabowo had admitted his wrong doings in the abductions of more
than 20 political activists early this year and said he would be
responsible for the cases.
</P>
<P>
Some local newspapers reported that Prabowo may also involved
in other criminal cases such as rioting in May in Jakarta and
other cities during which about 1,200 people were killed and more
than 5,000 shops and buildings were damaged or burned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
