<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Floods Still Mean Great Effort (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The floodwater may not seem so
threatening, but it is too early to say it's been defeated.
</P>
<P>
The 7th flood crest on the upper reaches of the Yangtze has
passed, with the water level of Chongqing hitting a record high of
183.21 meters, and the flow rate 58,000 cubic meters per second at
4 p.m. on Sunday. Authorities say that water levels on the middle
and lower reaches will not hit historical highs.
</P>
<P>
Water levels at the Yichang-Shishou section on the middle and
lower reaches have risen while the water receded slowly on
sections downstream at Jianli and Dongting and Poyang lakes, the
State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters told Xinhua
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The water level will remain high for a period of time on the
middle and upper reaches of the Yangtze, a headquarters official
said, and when the water ebbs, more dike slides, leaks, or even
breaches will appear.
</P>
<P>
According to a CCTV evening report, the dikes at Jianli and
Honghu have the greatest number of problems.
</P>
<P>
The 6th flood crest on the Yangtze passed Nanjing in Jiangsu
Province today with a water level of 9.95 meters at the Xiaguan
measuring point, 0.27 meter below the record level.
</P>
<P>
The flood crest on the Songhua River passed Harbin, the capital
of Heilongjiang Province, at 7:00 p.m. Sunday, with a level of
120.89 meters and a flow rate of 17,400 cubic meters per
second. It dropped to 120.84 meters at 2:00 p.m. today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Official on Financial Sector's Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A high-level financial
official of Singapore Monday announced that efforts to achieve
Year 2000 readiness in Singapore's financial sector are well on
track.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS)
Koh Yong Guan told a press conference here that Singapore's
financial sector has been preparing for Year 2000 since early 1997
and the MAS is confident that the financial system as a whole will
be resilient in the transition to Year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The Year 2000 problem is expected to cause many computers
worldwide to misread Year 2000 as 1900 because of their
incapability to read more than the two last digits of the year. As
this will lead to system failures, many Asian stock exchanges have
been upgrading their systems to make sure they are millennium
compliant.
</P>
<P>
Koh Yong Guan said one of the major concerns in the financial
area is to prepare the financial sector for Year 2000,
emphasizing that "getting ready for Year 2000 is the one of the
biggest immediate challenges facing the financial industry
throughout the world."
</P>
<P>
He said the MAS is taking decisive steps to co-ordinate
industry-wide Year 2000 compliance and has mapped out supervisory
measures to restrict the activities of those who can not meet
MAS's standards for Year 2000 readiness.
</P>
<P>
The Managing Director said a series of Year 2000 readiness test
has been scheduled for various industries, spelling out the tests
both under work and plans in financial sector.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Stock Exchange of Singapore (SES) had
just successfully completed a test on its trading system for Year
2000 readiness on Sunday and the Singapore International Money
Exchange (SIMEX) and the electronic payment system (MEPS) has been
scheduled to undergo a test respectively in October and in the
fourth quarter of this year. The entire financial sector will be
undergoing a Year 2000 readiness test in the first quarter of
1999.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday SES conducted a test run of its trading system
simulating the first day of business in the New millennium.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the test, which involved the 33 member firms of
the SES, several authorized trading centers, approved foreign
brokers, participants of the Bond Quotation System, trading
computers were set to believe that January 3, 2000, -- the first
business day of the new millennium -- had arrived.
</P>
<P>
Closing data from last Friday, August 21, was used for the test
run which was completed successfully, the SES said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
