<HEADLINE> Flood Fight Still Mean Great Effort (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More relief materials are being sent to flooded areas. By
Saturday night, 2.7 billion yuan (325.3 million U.S. dollars)
worth of donations from the Ministry of Civil Affairs, the Red
Cross Society of China, and the All-China Charity Federation had
been sent.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji recently said he was greatly concerned about
relief supplies, especially clothing and shelter, for the
Northeast, after 13,450 tents, 20,000 life vests, and
cotton-padded clothing was delivered by the State Flood Control
and Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The General Office of the State Council has demanded stricter
management of donations and the Ministry of Civil Affairs has
guaranteed that every penny of the relief funds will be used for
flood victims.
</P>
<P>
The prevention of epidemic disease is becoming more important
in flood-stricken areas. Minister of Health Zhang Wenkang has said
that infectious diseases like snail fever are a threat and that
the incidence of intestinal diseases, dysentery, hepatitis, and
colds is greater than last year.
</P>
<P>
The major problem is a shortage of funds and medicine, Zhang
says, and the problem could become worse in the next three months,
which is usually the peak period for epidemics. There are now
three problems: access to drinking water, disposing of rubbish,
and removing human waste, according to one member of a medical
working team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
