<HEADLINE> India Against Competitive Devaluation of Currencies: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee said Monday that he has strongly disfavored any
competitive devaluation of currencies.
</P>
<P>
In an interview given to Thai newspaper "The Nation", which was
made public here Monday evening, Vajpayee said that the East Asian
crisis was a pointer to the harm it can do to the financial and
capital markets.
</P>
<P>
This was one of the areas where India and the South East Asian
nations should be consulting continuously and looking at
strategies to prevent any crises, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have neither triggered competitive devaluation in the past
nor indulged in it despite pressures to do so," he further said.
</P>
<P>
India had weathered the crisis quite well so far though the
second wave was beginning to impact on India's economy. India was
affected by market sentiments and there was a heightened risk
assessment about Asia, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
