<HEADLINE> U.S. Experts Cite Disaster Aid Needs for Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- American military specialists
presented to Foreign Minister Abudus Samad Azad on Monday the
findings of a just-concluded assessment of humanitarian assistance
needs aimed at combating natural calamity in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
They demonstrated how the U.S. government could most
effectively provide assistance to Bangladesh during any future
disasters on request, a release from the External Publicity Wing
of the Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
A three-member team visited Dhaka, Rangpur, Bogra, Chittagong
and Cox's Bazar and after discussing with individuals and groups
of people in government departments and non-government
organizations (NGO), and recommended 11 types of projects for
capacity enhancement of the government to respond to natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
They presented an overview of their mission here and detailed
information concerning their activities, methods and
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
"The cardinal objective is to assist the government of
Bangladesh in increasing its ability to respond to natural
disasters," the release quoted the U.S. experts as telling the
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
The team told the minister that it had assessed in different
parts of Bangladesh the possible responses of both the government
and the NGO community to various types of disasters, including
cyclones, floods and earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
To help the Bangladeshi government improve its response to
disasters, the team offered a number of recommendations, including
U.S. donations of humanitarian equipment, exchange of experts on
humanitarian assistance, training of Bangladeshi officials in the
U.S., Bangladeshi-U.S. military exercises on humanitarian relief
and disaster-relief training simulations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. experts came here early this month under a memorandum
of understanding signed here late last month for a five-year
Humanitarian Assistance Needs Assessment project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
