<HEADLINE> France Repeats Call for Great Lakes Peace Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine Monday repeated France's call for holding an
international peace conference on the strife-torn Great Lakes
region in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The problems of the Democratic Republic of Congo, formerly
Zaire, were escalating, and several neighboring countries had
intervened to keep peace in the region, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the crisis in former Zaire did not involve just
one country, but five, six or seven countries.
</P>
<P>
"One can not but wish that these countries come to meet, and
agree upon what is the most urgent," said him.
</P>
<P>
These countries should try to resolve their differences and
become normal neighbors again, he said.
</P>
<P>
The idea of holding an international conference on the Great
Lakes region was first proposed by Burundi in 1994 and afterwards
pushed by French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
These countries all have problems with refugees and a lack of
infrastructure which could only be solved by combining their
efforts, he said.
</P>
<P>
France, along with other western countries like the United
States, Britain and Belgium, were ready, in one way or another, to
help these countries to get out of this vicious cycle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
