<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hyundai Motor's Labor Dispute Settled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The labor and management of
Hyundai Motor Co. have reached an agreement on layoffs, ending a
prolonged labor dispute at the nation's largest auto maker.
</P>
<P>
The accord came after both sides agreed on the number and terms
of layoffs in talks mediated by the government.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Hyundai will lay off only 277 workers,
sharply down from the original proposal of 1,538, with the
remaining 1,261 workers to be sent on 18 months unpaid leave,
including six months of retraining.
</P>
<P>
The company will give the 277 workers severance payments amounting
to seven to nine months' wages and opportunities to be rehired by
Hyundai Motor or other Hyundai subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
The management also agreed to drop damage and violence charges it
filed against unionists after the company returns to normal operation.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the compromise, production at Hyundai's Ulsan
factories is expected to return to normal after a suspension of more
than a month.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai's 26,000 union workers began the strike on July 20
this year in protest against the company's plan to lay off 1,538
workers and operations of Hyundai's factories has virtually been
at a standstill since then.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai Motor, which is capable of producing 1.65 million
vehicles per year and has 36,700 workers, has trimmed 6,100
workers through early retirement programs.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai claimed that the strike had cost 690 million dollars in
production losses, while its parts suppliers have suffered losses
of 566 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Hyundai case has widely been considered as a litmus test
for the economic reforms of the Kim Dae-jung government.
</P>
<P>
Creation of a more flexible labor market is one goal of the
reforms that the economically plagued nation had promised the
International Monetary Fund in return for a rescue loan of 57
billion dollars last December.
</P>
<P>
"On the occasion of the compromise, the company will take the
lead in establishing new labor-management relations as well as try
to minimize the number of workers to be laid off in the future,"
Hyundai Motor chairman Chung Mong-kyu said,
</P>
<P>
Hyundai labour leader Kim Kwang-shik said the accord has paved
the way for both labor and management to survive together in
mutual trust.
</P>
<P>
Labor Minister Lee Ki-ho hailed the compromise, saying, "It
marked a starting point in creating a new labor-management
culture."
</P>
<P>
However, some observers criticized the pact as too pro-labor,
arguing that the government has failed to show its will to
guarantee a flexible labor market, considered crucial to luring
foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts cautioned that the labor-management standoff was
not over as the pact must be approved by union members.
</P>
<P>
The Hyundai labor union plans to put the accord to a vote
soon. Some union workers were angered at union leaders for
accepting a minimum level of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
The Korea Employers' Federation said it was regrettable that
the Hyundai case had been settled by political logic as it had set
a bad example, which would affect other businesses negatively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
