<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Displeased With Pakistan's Effort to Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi Monday voiced Tehran's displeasure towards Islamabad's
"unsatisfactory" effort to release Iranian diplomats captured by
the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
"The work of Pakistan concerning the fate of kidnaped Iranian
diplomats were not worthy of being explained," Kharrazi told
visiting Pakistani Minister of State for Foreign Affairs Siddique
Khan Kanju, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Iranian government and people expected the
immediate release of the Iranian diplomats and the IRNA reporter
kidnaped by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Iran said that the Taliban forces kidnaped 11 Iranian
diplomats and an IRNA reporter earlier this month when the
fundamentalist group took control Mazari Sharif, the main
stronghold of the Iran-backed opposition.
</P>
<P>
Before the fall of Mazari Sharif to the Taliban's hands, he
said, Iran has asked Pakistan, a strong supporter of Taliban, to
get guarantee from the Taliban for the safety of the Iranian
consulate general in the city and its staff members.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister noted that the Taliban should
answer the question why they occupied the Iranian consulate by
force and kidnaped its staff members who have diplomatic
privileges.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban denied that they have captured any
Iranian diplomats from the city, saying that the Iranian
consulate was evacuated when their forces arrived there.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister stated that the telephone
contacts of the Iranian consulate were recorded, which proved the
existence of the Iranian diplomats in the consulate when the
Taliban fighters forced into it.
</P>
<P>
Any claim by the Taliban against the fact was a "mere lie," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi stressed that Iran's policy towards Afghanistan was
always based on non-interference in the Afghan internal affairs
and assistance to establish peace in that country.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that a lasting peace could be established only
when a broad-based government comprising of all groups and
minorities is formed in the country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kanju briefed Kharrazi the efforts of his government to ensure
the release of the Iranians, saying that the Pakistani government
has made all-out efforts to help release the Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
He said that the objective of his visit to Iran was to assure
the Iranian people and government that Pakistan would make all
efforts to ensure the release of the Iranians.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan also believes that the Afghan issue has no military
solution and a lasting peace could be possible only through the
establishment of broad-based government with participation of all
groups and minorities, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani official arrived here Sunday night to submit a
message from Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to Iranian
President Mohammad Khatami. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
