<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Offers Reward on Information on Missing Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government
announced Monday a reward of 100,000 rupees (1,470 U.S. dollars)
for information on the whereabouts of the plane missing since
Friday morning as the search operation is continuing.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Tourism and Civil Aviation Ananda Prasad Dhungana
told the Lower House of Parliament Monday that the government has
decided to cover the expenditure of the family members and
relatives of those on board the ill-fated twin Otter aircraft
moving to Pokhara and other places.
</P>
<P>
The plane with 18 people abroad including three crew members
and three Indians lost contact five minutes after it took off at
11:10 a.m. Friday in Jomsom, western Nepal.
</P>
<P>
It was scheduled to arrive in Pokhara, 80 kilometers away, at
11:30.
</P>
<P>
Press reports here said that the family members and relatives
of those abroad became furious over the failure to track the plane
in the past few days, saying that the government was not taking
the issue seriously.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the search efforts by the four helicopters were
again interrupted by bad weather, as it rained and was foggy in
the targeted area, a duty officer at the Rescue and Coordination
Center of the capital's Tribhuvan International Airport told
Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said that the area is where Mt. Dhaulagiri I (8,167m.) and
Mt. Annapurna I (8,091m.) lie, the steep mountains make it really
hard for the search efforts.
</P>
<P>
The army and police are joining in the search operation
together with the local people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
