<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Not Consulted by U.S. on Missile Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
Monday categorically rejected allegations in the local media
suggesting that Pakistan had been consulted by the United States
on its missile attacks against alleged terrorist targets in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
These reports are "completely unfounded," a Foreign Ministry
spokesman said in a press release issued Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Foreign Ministry has instructed its
permanent representative at the U.N. to take up the violation of
Pakistan's airspace in the U.S. missile attacks on August 20 with
the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
On August 21, the U.S. charge d'affaires was summoned to the
Foreign Ministry and a protest was lodged on the presumption that
the missiles had overflown Pakistan's airspace in violation of the
international law, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest information, it was discovered that one
of the U.S. missiles landed in an uninhabited area near Shatinger
in Baluchistan, northwestern Pakistan, but it did not explode.
This confirms the basis on which the earlier presumptive protest
was lodged by Pakistan, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the missiles were fired from U.S. ships which
were 120 nautical miles from the Pakistan coast and well outside
the 12-mile limit of Pakistan's territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
Reports in local English newspapers said that an unexploded
cruise missile, fired by the U.S. marine from the Arabian Sea, was
found in the deserted area in Baluchistan on August 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
