<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Army on Alert at Border with Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Angolan army has been on alert
at its border with the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), with
fighter planes in some airports on stand-by order to prevent the
flames of war from spreading to its own territory.
</P>
<P>
The country's military sources said Angolan army has made
reinforcement especially in the enclave province of Cabinda,
which is bordering the Congo Province in southwest DRC where the
fighting is extremely tense.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government has reportedly sent a 1,000-strong army
to the DRC to join the battle in defending the capital Kinshasa.
However, there is no confirmation from the military side.
</P>
<P>
Angola firmly supports Laurent Kabila, president of the DRC,
in putting down the armed rebellion by Tutsi soldiers. It had
urged the meeting of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) defense ministers to adopt a resolution on providing DRC
with military assistance.
</P>
<P>
Angola's opposition, the National Union for Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA), had taken advantage of the territory of former
Zaire as its military base, and the government is afraid of any
such recurrence.
</P>
<P>
President Eduardo dos Santos, who has cut short a holiday in
Brazil due to instability at home and in the region, noted that
his country is very worried over the situation in the neighboring
DRC.
</P>
<P>
Countries in the Great Lakes region should help each other to
promote peaceful co-existence, he said, adding no country is
allowed to use its own territory as a base to sabotage the
stability in other countries.
</P>
<P>
Angola and the DRC share over 1,000 kilometers of border. The
former Zaire under the late president Mobuto Sese Seko has
offered UNITA great help and allowed the former rebel movement to
set up military bases on its land.
</P>
<P>
During Kabila's armed struggle against Mobuto Sese Seko, the
Angolan government sent an army of about 5,000 men to help
Kabila. Angola and the DRC had signed an agreement on security
and defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
