<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seaborne Shipment Dominates HK's External Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Seaborne trade accounted for
46 percent of Hong Kong's external trade during the first half of
1998, the government figures show.
</P>
<P>
The Census and Statistics Department released here Monday that
26 percent of Hong Kong's total value of external trade was
transported by land, another 22 percent by air, and the rest by
river, and postal parcels.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of 1998, shipment by ocean amounted to
634.3 billion HK dollars (81 billion U.S. dollars), down 7.1
percent over the same period in 1997. Shipment by land and air
also declined slightly.
</P>
<P>
The United States remained the leading destination for Hong
Kong's exports by ocean, taking in 34 percent of the total in
value terms in the first half of this year. Japan was the largest
supplier of Hong Kong's seaborne imports, accounting for a share
of 22 percent in value terms.
</P>
<P>
Exports by air to the United States made up for 26 percent of
Hong Kong's total exports by air between January and June in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
