<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading US Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Monday:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Russian President Boris Yeltsin dismissed his new team of
economic reformers and reinstalled Victor S. Chernomyrdin as Prime
Minister, just five months after he derided Chernomyrdin as a
spent force and cast him out of the government. Yeltsin offered no
explanation for his decision, which raised fresh doubts about the
Kremlin's commitment to tough economic reforms and unsettling
questions about President Yeltsin's ability to govern.
</P>
<P>
-- On the day in January that the accusations about Monica
Lewinsky and U.S. President Bill Clinton became public, one set of
advisers -- the lawyers -- wanted Clinton to be vague in his
public responses and by no means say the word "sexual." The other
set -- the political team -- pressed for early candor. The fight
over strategy reflects the ongoing tension inside the White House
and inside the President.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. House Speaker Newt Gingrich said Sunday the House
likely will seek evidence from all of Kenneth W. Starr's
investigations -- not just the results of the inquiry into
President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky -- before
determining whether to launch an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
-- After days of steady march toward Kinshasa, Rwandan-backed
Congolese rebels fighting to oust President Laurent Kabila have
bogged down southwest of the capital city, where government forces
backed by Angola and Zimbabwe reportedly recaptured a key rebel
supply base.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Global Markets face additional uncertainty, analysts say,
after Russian President Boris Yeltsin dismissed his government and
installed Victor Chernomyrdin, whom Yeltsin ousted in March, as
acting prime minister. Worries about spreading economic turmoil
hit Spanish and German stocks on Friday and affected currencies
from Mexico's peso to the Canadian dollar. Investors sought
perceived havens like U.S. Treasurys. 
</P>
