<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DRC Cease-Fire Urgent, Says Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- No time should be lost in
bringing about a cease-fire in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC), South African President Nelson Mandela said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We should lose no time in ensuring that the cease-fire takes
place," South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Mandela as
saying in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Mandela made the remarks after meeting Nigerian leader General
Abdulsalam Abubakar, who is in South Africa for a three-day
visit.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Southern African Development Community (SADC)
Sunday called for a cease-fire and troop standstill in the DRC
after an emergency summit called by Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he informed Organization of African Unity
Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim earlier in the day about
SADC's stance.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo would brief Mandela
during the day on ways to bring about a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
"As soon as I get that briefing today, I will be in communication
with him (Salim)," Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the role of Angolan forces in the DRC conflict, he
said Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos had indicated that
he favored a cessation of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
"They (Angolan forces) have taken Kitona from the rebels, but
President dos Santos made a statement where he said they were not
going to advance from Kitona because they want a cease-fire and
negotiations."
</P>
<P>
This was a very healthy attitude, said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Angola was the only SADC country absent from Sunday's summit.
</P>
<P>
Mandela reiterated there should be coordination between SADC's
search for peace in the DRC with initiatives headed by Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
"The minister (Nzo) will work out modalities as to how that
coordination should take place."
</P>
<P>
Mandela added: "It was proposed yesterday (Sunday) that South
Africa, Mozambique and Tanzania, because of their experience in
negotiating settlements, should take the initiative in the
formation of a mechanism to ensure that we achieve an immediate
standstill in the DRC."
</P>
<P>
Mandela said the conflict in the DRC would be discussed with
Abubakar in follow-up meetings during his visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
