<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Nigeria Should Renew Ties: Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Nigeria
should renew bilateral relations and speak with one voice on
problems facing Africa, South African President Nelson Mandela
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"It is important for us to renew our relationship because
those ties can only be in the interest of the continent of
Africa," Mandela was quoted by South African Press Association as
saying after meeting Nigerian leader Abdulsalam Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
He said he expected a strengthening of ties between the two
countries, also after the scheduled civilian takeover of the
Nigerian government in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar said South Africa and Nigeria had a long-standing
history of relations marked by respect and understanding.
</P>
<P>
"We share some common values about how we see Africa being
developed," he said.
</P>
<P>
The natural and human resources of both countries could
contribute much to the upliftment on the continent, Abubakar
said.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar is on a three-day state visit to South Africa, the
first by a Nigerian head of state.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two most influential countries in Africa
had been strained since 1995 when Mandela led an international
call for sanctions against Nigeria following the execution of
several human rights activists.
</P>
<P>
Mandela described Abubakar as an old friend, saying South
Africa welcomed his coming to power on June 9 after the death of
his predecessor Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and other African countries were confident that
Abubakar was the right man to restore democracy in Nigeria, said
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident this is the leader who is going to help us
to achieve that," he added.
</P>
<P>
The steps Abubakar had announced to return his country to
civilian rule were in the interest of the whole continent as
Nigeria had the largest population in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mandela welcomed an independent electoral commission Abubakar
had set up, as well as moves to open the field for all political
parties in that country.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar said he had consulted widely, also with world
leaders, on the best way to attain democracy in Nigeria. Ways to
boost the Nigerian economy were also under consideration.
</P>
<P>
"I hope, come May 29, 1999, we will hand over to an elected
government," Abubakar said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
