<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Entrusts Chernomyrdin with Forming Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
on Monday gave Acting Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin a clear
mandate to reorganize the government and formulate its programs.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin had "the full trust of the president" in selecting
members of his cabinet and making plans, the Itar-Tass news agency
cited Yeltsin's spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government's line-up and programs were discussed by Yeltsin
and Chernomyrdin in the Kremlin earlier on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to Yastrzhembsky, Chernomyrdin was open to
cooperation with all political and public groups.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was nominated as acting prime minister by Yeltsin
on Monday following the sacking of the entire government headed by
Sergei Kiriyenko on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, the former prime minister who was dismissed by
Yeltsin five months ago, agreed to his appointment as prime
minister again, but laid down certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
He insisted on having full personal control over the
appointment of all government ministers, including the heads of
"power ministries" and key economic agencies.
</P>
<P>
In a television address to the nation on Monday, Yeltsin said
that Chernomyrdin would be his preferred successor in the
presidential elections in the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Describing Chernomyrdin as a "heavyweight", Yeltsin said his
experience might improve the situation in the country, which had
been seriously affected by the world financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
