<HEADLINE> Bin Laden Never Sets Foot on Philippines: Military Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Chief of Staff of the
Armed Forces Joselin Nazareno denied here Monday a local news
report that international terrorist suspect Bin Laden was sighted
in Mindanao, the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"This guy Bin Laden has never been in the Republic of the
Philippines," Nazareno said in a hastily called press conference
to quash the report that the multi-millionaire Saudi Arabian was
seen in Mindanao following the deadly bombings of the U.S.
embassies in Kenya and Tanzania earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Bin Laden was suspected by the United States to have been
linked with the bombings.
</P>
<P>
The people might mistook Jamal Kalifa, the brother-in-law of
Bin Laden, because they look alike, Nazareno said, adding that
Kalifa married a Filipino and came to the Philippines before the
coming of the Pope about so many years back.
</P>
<P>
Nazareno was referring to the visit of the John Paul II in
Manila in January 1995 when authorities discovered a plot to
assassinate the pontiff.
</P>
<P>
But when the plot was exposed before the assassination attempt,
Kalifa went out of the country and never returned.
</P>
<P>
Nazareno said terrorism is an international crime and almost
all countries are against it, adding the Philippine military has
taken precautionary measures to protect the American embassy here.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the Bureau of Immigration also confirmed that
it does not have any record of the arrival or departure of Bin
Laden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
