<HEADLINE> Myanmar Minister Meets NLD Party Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar Minister of Home Affairs
Colonel Tin Hlaing met here with two top officials of the National
 League for Democracy (NLD) party for talks Monday, according to
an official Information Sheet.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came three days after the expiry of a deadline set
by the NLD to the ruling State Peace and Development Council
(SPDC) for a demand that parliament elected in the May 1990
Multi-Party General Election be convened for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The two NLD officials are members of the party's Central
Executive Committee U Than Tun and U Soe Myint.
</P>
<P>
The talks were described as "frank and cordial."
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, SPDC First Secretary Lieutenant-General Khin
Nyunt had a 45-minute meeting with NLD Chairman U Aung Shwe. Khin
Nyunt said that it was "the first in a series of meetings with the
NLD," while the NLD described it as an "informal meeting."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NLD has decided to convene in the near future a
National Parliament elected in the 1990 General Election. A total
of 93 political parties took part in the election.
</P>
<P>
However, the government warned that "such an action by any
individual political party would be in contravention of Myanmar
Law and seems designed to derail the ongoing discussions between
the government and the NLD." 
</P>
