<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Retail Sales Fall by 16 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's total retail sales
in June recorded a double-digit decline from a year earlier as
consumers were reluctant to spend in economic woes.
</P>
<P>
The value of total retail sales in June, estimated at 15.9
billion HK dollars (2 billion U.S. dollars), decreased by 16
percent compared with the same month of 1997, the Census and
Statistics Department released here Monday.
</P>
<P>
After discounting the effect of inflation, total retail sales
fell by 16 percent in volume.
</P>
<P>
Department stores were hit hardest, with sales slumping 29
percent in value and 30 percent in volume in June, while
supermarkets posted a two-percent gain in value of sales, and a
moderate 4 percent decline in volume.
</P>
<P>
Sales of clothing and footwear, motor vehicles, miscellaneous
consumer goods, jewelry, watches and clocks, and valuable gifts
all registered significant declines in the month.
</P>
<P>
Total retail sales in the first six months of 1998 decreased by
14 percent in value and 15 percent in volume compared with the
first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman said Monday that retail sales continued
to record a double-digit decline in June, mainly due to the
prevailing subdued consumer sentiment and the setback in inbound
tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
