<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Accuses S. Africa of Behind-Curtain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic of
Congo Monday accused South Africa of "behind-curtain manoeuvres",
saying a signal from a South African Airways (SAA) aircraft was
intercepted in its eastern town of Goma.
</P>
<P>
"We learnt yesterday (Sunday) evening from different reliable
sources that a South African airplane from SAA was intercepted by
our radios, asking for permission to land in Goma at around 6
p.m. (1700 GMT) yesterday," DRC Justice Minister Mwenze Kongolo
said in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
"We informed the South African government and we are still
waiting for their explanation," Kongolo was quoted by South
African Press Association (SAPA) as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Congo believes that such behind-curtain manoeuvres are not
likely to bring peace in this country," he added.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Ministry spokesman Machiel van Niekerk
denied there was a South African plane in the Rwandan-held DRC
town.
</P>
<P>
"As far as we know, there is no such plane in Goma," he noted.
</P>
<P>
SAPA quoted government sources as saying that two South
African Air Force Boeing 707s were in Kinshasa to evacuate
Tanzanian military instructors caught between government troops
and rebels.
</P>
<P>
A military Hercules C130 also landed in Kinshasa Sunday night
to evacuate equipment. The Tanzanian troops were refusing to
leave without their equipment as they were afraid of looting.
</P>
<P>
Kongolo, who is in South Africa for peace talks with Ugandan
and Rwandan presidents, said the DRC would only engage in peace
talks after a complete and immediate withdrawal of Ugandan and
Rwandan troops from the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"They must not only stop hostilities, but also withdraw their
troops without delay," he said. "In such a case, Congo commits
itself to refrain from attacking the withdrawing troops."
</P>
<P>
Kongolo said troops from Zimbabwe and Angola, sent to support
the DRC government, would not be asked to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
"We are a legitimate government. We have the right to have any
troops that we want.
</P>
<P>
"Angola and Zimbabwe are part of that right. They are there
because we invited them to come. They will go when we agree with
them that they go."
</P>
<P>
Kongolo said the two countries had helped to bring Rwanda and
Uganda closer to the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
"It was important that Rwanda and Uganda felt Congo was not
alone, Congo has friends who can come and help, so that they can
think twice about their position. I believe that they thought
twice."
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Development Community (SADC) Sunday
called for a ceasefire and troop standstill in the DRC, saying
this was approved by all role players who attended the SADC
emergency summit in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Kongolo said the DRC had made it clear during the discussions
that a ceasefire meant a complete and immediate withdrawal of
Ugandan and Rwandan troops.
</P>
<P>
"This definition went without protest from the countries
present at the meeting," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kongolo said it was now up to South African President Nelson
Mandela as SADC chairman, and the Organization of African Unity
Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim, to put in place steps to
effect a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he had talked to Salim Monday morning and would
speak to him again soon.
</P>
<P>
He said no time should be lost in bringing about a ceasefire
in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Kongolo said the rebels were believed to be on their way to
Matadi, a few hundred kilometers away from the capital, Kinshasa.
</P>
</TEXT>
