<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Denies Reversion of Stand on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu denied Monday that he has given up his demand
that the Palestinian National Council (PNC) convene to annul the
clauses of the Palestinian Covenant that call for Israel's
destruction.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released by his office in Jerusalem, Netanyahu
stressed that any agreement with the Palestinians was contingent
upon the annulment of parts of the Palestinian Covenant.
</P>
<P>
The statement disclosed that Netanyahu discussed this issue
with the U.S. President Bill Clinton last week.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's office issued the statement after local daily
Haaretz reported Monday that Netanyahu has for the first time
officially reversed his stand on revising the Palestinian
Covenant.
</P>
<P>
It said the concession was contained in a document that was
conveyed in the past few days by Netanyahu's senior adviser and
attorney Yitzhak Molcho to Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been stalled since
early last year mainly due to the dispute over the scope of
Israeli second troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel has reportedly accepted the 13.1 percent pullback plan
put forward by the U.S., but it demands the Palestinian side agree
to turn 3 percent of West Bank into natural reserves and that the
PNC amend the Palestinian Covenant before signing an agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
