<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Telecom to Deploy New Internet Billing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- China's largest public
telecommunications service provider, China Telecom, will launch a
new Internet billing system in September.
</P>
<P>
The system will be jointly developed by China Telecom and the
world's computer software giant, Microsoft Corp. A cooperation
agreement was recently signed between the Data Communication
Bureau of China Telecom and Microsoft (China) Co., Ltd.
</P>
<P>
According to Ye Yongdong, a senior Data Communication Bureau
engineer in charge of the project, the new billing operation will
be designed on the Microsoft Commercial Internet System (MCIS) 2.0
platform, which was launched last week in Beijing, and on Windows
NT.
</P>
<P>
The billing system is expected to have the capacity of
authentication of billing on access and information
interfaces, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
China Telecom will market the system on China Net and among
Internet service providers (ISP).
</P>
<P>
Officials say this joint development program is part of the
implementation of the framework agreement between China Telecom
and Microsoft signed in March.
</P>
<P>
The framework pact was aimed at facilitating China Internet
and Intranet services. And aside from the billing system project,
the agreement encompasses joint development of China Telecom
Internet Explorer, and exchange of Internet related technologies.
</P>
<P>
The newly introduced MCIS 2.0 is a group of server applications
designed to make it easier for Internet commercial service
providers to deploy virtual networking and surfing, administrate
Internet, Intranet and commercial websites, and provide
telecommunications service such as e-mail, news releasing and
NetMeeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
