<HEADLINE> Modahl Threatens BAF with Ultimatum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, August 24 (Xinhua) -- British runner Diane Modahl on
Monday threatened to take further legal action against British
Athletic Federation (BAF) unless the BAF offered her a
satisfactory compensation in seven days.
</P>
<P>
The bankrupt BAF is sued by Modahl, who asked for 800,000 U.S.
dollars in compensation after being sent home from the 1994
Commonwealth Games for her allege failure in a doping test.
</P>
<P>
Modahl later successfully fought a four-year ban that ensued
and had competed in the 800 meters for Britain at last week's
European Championships here.
</P>
<P>
"I have now instructed my lawyers that, in the absence of some
sensible proposals from BAF, the case has to continue and a trial
date has to be fixed at the first possible opportunity," said
Modahl.
</P>
<P>
She said, "The administrators have a clear choice. Either they
persuade the other creditors to fund the legal costs of fighting
the case to trial or they continue discussions with us with a
view to resolving all outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
"But I cannot be expected to keep my claim on hold and so, as
from September 1, my lawyers will be taking the necessary steps
to advance the proceedings." 
</P>
</TEXT>
