<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka to Seek Aid for Post-Flood Rehabilitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government on
Monday decided to seek international assistance for post-flood
rehabilitation programs in the country, the official BSS news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a meeting chaired by Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina, who reviewed the overall flood situation in the
country and directed officials concerned for coordination of
relief and rehabilitation programs to monitor relief activities
and assess the damages in the flood-hit areas.
</P>
<P>
The government would seek international assistance for
agricultural rehabilitation, the repair of educational
institutions, railways, roads, for procurement of foodgrain and
medicines, sinking of tubewells and other rehabilitation programs.
</P>
<P>
It also decided at the meeting to construct at least one flood
center at each of the country's 490 thanas (divisions) for the
flood-affected people, and Finance Minister Shah A.M.S. Kibria has
been given responsibility to assess the requirement of land and
the number of flood centers to be needed in the country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the road link between the capital city of Dhaka and
Chittagong, southeast Bangladesh, has been disrupted as the
flooding water has submerged the highway at many places, leaving
hundreds of buses and trucks stranded on the road, press reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The flood situation is deteriorating in 14 districts, including
Dhaka and its adjoining areas, but has improved in eight
districts, officials said.
</P>
<P>
As of Sunday, more than 18 million people in the country had
been affected by floods, and more than 95,000 people attacked by
diarrhea, with 62 deaths from the water-borne disease reported.
</P>
<P>
The flood-related death toll in the country as of Sunday stood
at 333. 
</P>
</TEXT>
