<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 875,000 Chinese Abroad for Private Purposes in January-June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Some 875,000 Chinese citizens
went abroad for private purposes during the first half of the
year, up 2.7 percent from the same period last year, according to
the Exit and Entry Administration under the Ministry of Public
Security.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the administration pointed out that some
550,000 of them were tourists, up 0.9 percent compared with the
first half last year.
</P>
<P>
Among the tourists, some 328,000, or 60 percent of the total,
were part of an organized tour, and the other 222,000, or some 40
percent, toured China's neighbouring countries or regions on their
own.
</P>
<P>
The official said that in the first six months, about 187,000
Chinese citizens went abroad to visit their relatives or friends,
up 20 percent from the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, 24,000 Chinese went abroad to study in
foreign universities, of which more than 21,000 went at their own
expense, and the rest were funded by the government or by their
work units.
</P>
<P>
He said that the administration gave approval to 31,200 Chinese
to settle down abroad, and to some 12,876 Chinese to act as
contract workers, of which 5,542 were exported by domestic labor
companies, and the rest organized by overseas employment offices.
</P>
<P>
Also, 73,000 Chinese gained approval to travel abroad on
business trips, to attend training courses, or to negotiate with
their foreign customers.
</P>
<P>
Along with three southest Asian countries, Russia, the United
States, Japan, and Australia topped the list as destinations for
Chinese citizens going overseas, with the number of Chinese
visiting these countries up to 87,000, 72,300, 35,000 and 22,300
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
