<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Power Stations Planned For Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANZHIHUA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A number of large power
stations, many much larger than the existing one, will be built
on the Yangtze River in the next century.
</P>
<P>
One of the projected facility will be on the upper reaches of
the Jinsha River, a tributary of the Yangtze, and will have a
designed capacity of 12 million kw.
</P>
<P>
At present, the Ertan Hydropower Station, located on the
Yalong River, a tributary of the Yangtze, is China's largest to be
completed in this century. With a designed capacity of 3.3 million
kw, the facility has gone into partial operation here in
Panzhihua City, Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The Ertan facility is often cited as a good example of
introducing international bidding, and the future projects will most
probably follow the Ertan example, experts say.
</P>
<P>
On another section of the Jinsha River, another huge plant with
a designed capacity of 5.2 million kw will be constructed.
</P>
<P>
On the Dadu River, also a Yangtze tributary, a 3.3 million kw
facility, the same size as the Ertan plant, is projected. An
estimated 100,000 to 150,000 people will have to be relocated to
pave the way for the project.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, over 20 more power stations will be built on the
Yalong River, the largest with a capacity of 3.6 million kw,
also larger than the Ertan facility.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, the Jinsha, Yalong and Dadu rivers, all
at the upper reaches of the Yangtze, have a combined water reserve
of over 120 million kw, accounting for one fourth of the country's
total. At present, only five million kw have been tapped.
</P>
<P>
The completion of these facilities will enable the power grids
of southwest, eastern and northern China to become connected,
helping the country end its history of electricity shortages,, and
substantially reducing the threat of flooding, according to
experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
