<HEADLINE> Myanmar Government Hopes Further Talks with NLD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar government hopes
sincerely to continue meetings with the National League for
Democracy (NLD), according to an official information sheet issued
here Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The information sheet said that the government encourages the
NLD to join in a meaningful discussion, and to avoid actions that
would disrupt national peace, stability and development.
</P>
<P>
"The Myanmar government noted with concern the decision by the
NLD to convene a national parliament. Such an action by any
individual political party would be in contravention of Myanmar
law, and seems designed to derail the ongoing discussions between
the government and the NLD," it said.
</P>
<P>
Last talks between NLD Chairman U Aung Shwe and First Secretary
of the Myanmar State Peace and Development Council (SPDC)
Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt took place on last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is the government's view that those talks marked the
beginning of a period of conciliation, cooperation and mutual help
in building a better future for the people of Myanmar," the
document said.
</P>
<P>
"The government would be disappointed if radical and
provocative actions by NLD leaders made further discussions
impossible," it added.
</P>
<P>
"During the current economic crisis in Asia, it is more
important than ever for all Myanmar citizens to work together for
the good of the people, rather than to play politics," it
stressed.
</P>
<P>
On June 23, the NLD leaders set a deadline for a demand to the
ruling SPDC to convene a national parliament within 60 days, but
the government made no response to it.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by the NLD on August 21, the
NLD will convene a national parliament in the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
