<HEADLINE> Nepal to Stress Aid to Poor Countries at NAM Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Nepal will especially
emphasize increasing development aid to the least developed
countries at the 12th summit of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM)
scheduled for next month, Foreign Ministry officials said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Special Secretary Narayan S. Thapa and
Undersecretary Mohan Krishna Shrestha said that developed
countries have not fulfilled their commitment to providing 0.7
percent of their gross domestic product (GDP) to the least
developed countries.
</P>
<P>
They said that debt is a very big problem for the least
developed countries and Nepal will ask for the consideration of
this problem.
</P>
<P>
Nepal will also raise the issues of south-south cooperation and
north-south dialogue at the summit to be held in Durban, South
Africa, they said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala, who is scheduled to leave
for Durban later this month, will meet leaders of some countries
including the Gulf countries where many Nepalese go for jobs, they
said.
</P>
<P>
NAM, formed in September 1961, has 113 members in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
