<HEADLINE> Philippine Coconut Exports Seen At 1.8 Million Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines coconut exports
this year are expected to equal last year's 1.8 million metric
tons despite the El Nino and La Nina weather phenomena, an
official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Coconut Authority Deputy Administrator Norberto
Boceta said that coconut is not as affected as other crops by the
lingering drought caused by the El Nino and the arrival of the La
Nina which brings about devastating floods.
</P>
<P>
"Production would go down either in the latter part of the year
or in the early part of 1999, but the figures (for exports) I have
up to July still look good," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said this year's coconut exports target took into
consideration of the January-July exports which have already gone
up to 1.3 million metric tons, up by 21 percent from the year-ago
level.
</P>
<P>
In terms of value, exports earnings also rose by 15 percent
from 482 million pesos (11.2 million U.S. dollars) in 1997 to 556
million pesos (12.9 million dollars) during the period.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is the largest coconut exporter in Southeast
Asia and one of the biggest in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
