<HEADLINE> Flu Affects Perkins' Preparation for Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Australia's world record
holder Kieren Perkins said in Sydney on Monday that a recent
illness has disrupted his preparation plan for next month's
Commonwealth Games in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Perkins, an Olympic swimming gold medallist, has been hit by
an influenza, which may affect the defence of his Commonwealth
Games 1,500 meters freestyle title.
</P>
<P>
The swimmer, who missed training last week, said: "The biggest
problem we've got at the moment is that if I get back into it too
hard, too fast, I could have a relapse."
</P>
<P>
Perkins set the existing world record for 1,500 meters when he
won the 1994 Commonwealth Games title in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Perkins will travel to Perth on Tuesday to join the Australian
Commonwealth Games swimming team for three days of training.
</P>
