<HEADLINE> Rwandan, Ugandan Troops Must Pull out of Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) would only engage in peace talks after troops from
Rwanda and Uganda withdrew from the country, DRC Justice Minister
Mwenze Kongolo said Monday in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
He said troops from Angola and Zimbabwe, who are supporting
the DRC government, would not be required to leave the country,
according to South African Press Association.
</P>
<P>
"We are a legitimate government, we have the right to have any
troops we want."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe and Angola sent troops and arms to support DRC
President Laurent Kabila against a rebel uprising allegedly
backed by Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Development Community (SADC) Sunday
called for a ceasefire and troop standstill in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The SADC was holding an emergency summit in Pretoria to search
for a peaceful solution to the conflict in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Kongolo said a signal from a South African plane was
intercepted in Goma recently which reported that Goma was a
Rwandan-held part of the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Kongolo said the DRC had informed the South African government
about the incident and was awaiting an explanation for the presence of
a South African aircraft over its territory.
</P>
<P>
Kongolo is in South Africa for talks with presidents of Rwanda
and Uganda. He was sent in Kabila's plane as Kabila was
reportedly ordered by his doctor to rest. 
</P>
