<HEADLINE> Normal Life Paralyzed in India's Bihar State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Nornal life was paralyzed in
Bihar State of northern India as a strike organized by the
Rashtriya Janata Dal (National People's Party) began Monday
morning to protest against the raids of the Central Bureau of
Investigation (CBI) on the State Chief Minister Rabri Devi's
residence.
</P>
<P>
CBI raided the Chief Minister's official residence and other
related places at the same time last Thursday to find out illegal
assets belonging to the Chief Minister's husband Laloo Yadav for
his alleged involved in a multi-crore fodder scam.
</P>
<P>
The State Capital Patna wore a deserted look as shops and
business establishments were closed and vehicles kept off the
roads.
</P>
<P>
Train services were affected as protesters squatted on the rail
tracks near Patna railway station.
</P>
<P>
Laloo Supporters asserted that the CBI's raids was a biased and
politically motivated action against the Opposition in the country
and demanded removal of CBI Joint Director U. N. Biswas from the
fodder scam probe.
</P>
<P>
Arson and violence also marked the dawn-to-dusk strike.
Supporters of the strike set two bogies of a train on fire and
broke window panes and damaged a machine at the ticket counter at
Patna railway junction, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
A stampede-like situation was witnessed near Begusarai railway
station when passengers including some army soldiers beat up
strike supporters who attempted to intercept the train's movement.
Five people suffered injuries in the clash, the sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
