<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan has asked for Israeli agreement on increasing
the passenger flights to ten and opening a cargo flight between
Amman and Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
Jordan also wishes to explore the prospects of Jordanian planes
flying over the Ben Gurion Airport near Tel Aviv until the
Palestinian Dahaniya airport in Gaza is opened.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed Jordanian sources said that Jordan has also
demanded Israel allow the number of travelers carried by Jordanian
aircrafts between Jordan and Israel to rise from 250 to 450 people
a week.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- Oman's Liquefied Gas Company under construction in
the south of the country is scheduled to start exporting its
products in April 2000, the Arab daily Al Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The government revenues are expected to rise by 18 percent
after the liquefied gas project in Qalhat city of the Southern
Soor State is operated.
</P>
<P>
A company official has said that agreements have been reached
with several Asian firms for an annual export of 6 million tonnes
of liquefied gas, accounting for 90 percent of the plant's
production capacity.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's Port Said Investment Company for Regional
Development will invite tenders soon for implementing
infrastructure projects in an 11-square-kilometer area east of the
city, the Egyptian Alam Al Yom daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The tenders will be made public in the coming two months for
the projects with an estimated cost of 1.5 billion pounds (441
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Denmark has allocated 750 million Denmark krones (110
million dollars) for promoting the private sector in six
developing countries, including Egypt, the Egyptian Al Ahram daily
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the Danish Embassy in Cairo said the grant will be
offered to industrial companies in the areas of computers,
electronics, weaving and textile, food, engineering, educational
services and combating environmental pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
