<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Draft Laws Amended In Response to Public Opinions (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
The new draft of the law on village committees, whose primary
aim is to safeguard the autonomy of villagers over their own
affairs, incorporates more suggestions put forward by the public
after it was published last month.
</P>
<P>
According to the NPC Law Committee, because of the
participation of villagers, the procedures for village committee
elections and impeachment are now more detailed and easier to
enforce.
</P>
<P>
However, the committee told the legislators that many letters
differ on two major issues: relations between village committees
and local governments, and whether or not village committees
should be empowered to handle economic matters.
</P>
<P>
Some, mainly local government officials, said that township
governments should play a leadership role in relations with
village committees in order to increase the government's ability
to lead agriculture. The opposing side maintained that if village
committees are to be "led" by township governments, village
autonomy will only nominally exist.
</P>
<P>
The Law Committee agreed with the latter argument, and have
not accepted the "leadership" relations in the new draft, because
"it has not been found that village autonomy, practiced in China
for 10 years under the existing law, has in any way adversely
affected local government execution of its power according to law."
</P>
<P>
The existing law gave village committees the right to manage
collectively owned village economic entities. Some propose the
abolishment of this right, others insist on upholding it. The Law
Committee said that due to the complexity of the rural economy and
its position during this transitional period, the new draft will
retain the existing stipulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Hit New Low of More Than 12 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar hit the
downhill trail Monday, sliding under 58.00 U.S. cents for the
first time in more than 12 years.
</P>
<P>
The fall ignited market speculation of central bank
intervention in the foreign exchange market to prop up the ailing
domestic currency.
</P>
<P>
Yet the Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) appeared to be absent
from the market Monday, apparently content to monitor the
situation from the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts reiterated the RBA's past comments that
intervention was only likely if trade became disorderly, rather
than the steady slow decline noted in recent weeks and months.
</P>
<P>
The addition of Russia's deepening crisis to the existing Asian
economic turmoil was sending the Australian dollar to a bottom of
57.79 U.S. cents that surpassed its previous 1998 low of 58.00
U.S. cents and marked the currency's lowest point since 1986.
</P>
<P>
On July 28, 1986 the Australian dollar tumbled to 57.10 U.S.
cents, the record post-float low for the currency.
</P>
<P>
Analysts are now concerned that the Asian and Russian problems
will extend to emerging economies with severe and adverse impacts
on global growth and commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Australian dollar's link with the Japanese yen
has made a resurgence following a breakdown in the correlation
late last week.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed trading here at 84.00 yen, from
84.03 previously and it was at 1.0449 German marks from 1.0564.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
