<HEADLINE> NPC Uses Video Tapes for Law Enforcement Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- At the Fourth Meeting of the
Standing Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress (NPC)
here this morning, Vice-Chairman Zou Jiahua showed video tapes to
demonstrate the serious pollution problems in the seas along
China's coasts.
</P>
<P>
At 10:45 a.m. Zou stood at a rostrum in the Great Hall of the
People. Instead of delivering a speech, Zou said, "I would like to
have a video tape played for you to show the marine pollution."
</P>
<P>
Zou was to deliver a report to the NPC Standing Committee on
the implementation of China's Law on Marine Environment
Protection.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time China's top legislature watched a
video tape before their discussions.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the 15-minutes show, the 137 members of the NPC
Standing Committee including the chairman and vice-chairmen were
captivated by the scenes of increasing pollution on the seas.
</P>
<P>
On the bottom of the sea at Jiaozhou Bay there is no longer any
marine life; a dyeing enterprise in Shanghai is pouring black
sewage into the East China Sea; a beach at Dapeng Bay in the South
China Sea has become a waste area under pollutants from five
dyeing mills in Shenzhen City.
</P>
<P>
Zou said that since 1983 when China's Law on Marine Environment
Protection was promulgated, China has achieved progress in laws
concerning the marine environment.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, in some places marine pollution was
getting worse and laws were being ignored.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the worsening ocean environment along the coasts
has led to frequent environmental calamities.
</P>
<P>
"Ocean pollution has hindered economic and social
development in the coastal areas and constitutes a threat to
people's health," he said.
</P>
<P>
One member said that the video show helped him learn more about
the polluted situation on the seas along China's coasts and that
it was more persuasive than a report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
