<HEADLINE> Unexploded U.S. Missile Found in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 24 (Xinhua) -- An unexploded cruise missile
bearing U.S. markings was found Saturday near Basima, Kharan
district, Baluchistan province in northwestern Pakistan, two local
English newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Nation said that people in the village, about 10 kilometers
from Kharan town, reported to the district administration that a
long object was lying in the desert.
</P>
<P>
The administration's officials inspected the missile bearing
the mark of U.S.A. and called in a bomb disposal squad from
Quetta, provincial capital of Balochistan.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the news of cruise missile spread like a
jungle fire in the villages and panic gripped the people who have
already heard about the missile attack by the United States on
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The projectile was found on Saturday, two days after the U.S.
fired cruise missiles at alleged terrorist targets in Afghanistan
bordering the Baluchistan province.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another newspaper The Dawn said that local
authorities have ordered a massive evacuation as a precautionary
measure. The nearest resident settlement is just 12 kilometers
away from the missile landing site, the report said. 
</P>
