<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Soldiers Ordered to Stop Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has instructed its military training team in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) to stop its training mission
to avoid becoming embroiled in conflict in the central African
country.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who is on an official visit in Denmark, has admitted
that Tanzania has a few soldiers in the DRC whose assignment was
to train the national army of the central African country.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the National Danish News Agency Sunday,
Mkapa said Tanzanian soldiers have stopped training the DRC army,
because Tanzania does not want to be drawn into the conflict
militarily, local newspapers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The president, however, did not say whether or when the
Tanzanian soldiers will move back, or what they will be doing in
the DRC if they stay there.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa commended the efforts made by South African President
Nelson Mandela in bringing all parties involved in the conflict
to the negotiation table and expressed Tanzania's resolve to work
relentlessly for a political solution to the current volatile
situation in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
He did not rule out a consensus on a regional military
intervention, saying the priority should be an immediate
ceasefire irrespective of which army is involved. He said this
will be in the interest of regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa, who said the situation in the DRC is very worrisome,
once again cautioned that there will be no military solution to
the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said Tanzania will stretch its resources to the limit to
pursue peace and stability in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The president discounted allegations that there is rivalry
between South Africa and Zimbabwe and that the conflict might
lead to the collapse of the Southern African Development
Community.
</P>
<P>
There was no rivalry between South Africa and Zimbabwe, he
said, adding Tanzania is prepared to work with either of them to
reach a negotiated political settlement in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa's remarks came after Zimbabwe, which has sent troops to
bolster DRC President Laurent Kabila's forces on the western
front, boycotted a SADC meeting in South Africa called by Mandela
to discuss the crisis.
</P>
<P>
As the war between the rebel troops and the government is
escalating in the DRC, more than 500 refugees from the country
have fled into the Kigoma Region in west Tanzania since August 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Measures to Slow Deforestation Discussed in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The first substantive session of
the Intergovernmental Forum on Forests began here Monday to
discuss measures to slow deforestation.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day meeting of the forum will also try to have
background talks on possible elements and work toward consensus on
international mechanisms, such as a legally binding instrument to
be decided in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
Since the creation of the United Nations Intergovernmental
Panel on Forests in 1995 after the 1992 Earth Summit in Rio de
Janeiro, governments agreed on over 135 proposals for action
towards sustainable forest management.
</P>
<P>
How to put those proposals into action and track progress will
be among top items to be discussed at the meeting of the new
forum, which was established in June, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Among the key action proposals to be discussed at the forum are
national forest programs, criteria and indicators, trade and
environment, and international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Deforestation continued in the 1990s although reports prepared
for the forum session show significant progress since the Earth
Summit, both in improving national forest planning at the country
level, and in increasing international coordination.
</P>
<P>
Between 1991 and 1995, the world lost an average of 11.3
million hectares of net forest area annually, an area roughly the
size of Honduras, according to the Worldwatch Institute, based on
data from the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
