<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC to Pass Bill Prohibiting Land Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A bill on the prohibition of
landmines and laser blinding weapons was presented today for
approval to the fourth meeting of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
Entrusted by the State Council, vice-minister of foreign
affairs Zhang Deguang gave a detailed explanation at the meeting
of the reasons China should approve the Revised Provision
of Landmine Protocols and the Protocol of Prohibition of Use of
Laser Blinding Weapons, which are additional protocols to the
Convention on Certain Conventional Weapons signed in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the two protocols embody the attention
paid by the international community to humanitarianism, and the
protocols' contents do not go against relevant laws in China.
</P>
<P>
"The approval of the two protocols helps to safeguard China's
image in world peace, and accords with the demands of the country's
diplomacy and foreign policy and with the interests of its
national defence," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
China signed the Convention on Prohibition or Restriction on
the Use of Certain Conventional Weapons in September 1981, which
so far has 57 member states, and approved the treaty and its
three additional protocols in March 1982.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
