<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Increases in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Stock Exchange (NSE)
recorded an improved inflow of foreign direct investment
totalling 9.5 million U.S. Dollars in the first half of this
year.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the NSE said the figure represents an
increase of 64 percent compared with the corresponding period of
last year, the Business Corcord reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the NSE, the half year report noted, Nigerian companies
raised a total of 84.5 million Dollars through the issuance of
new shares as against 14.3 million Dollars in the first half of
last year.
</P>
<P>
NSE's Assistant Director General Alhaji Rasak Oladejo told the
newspaper that the political climate in the country was hazy
during the review period but high returns have continued to
attract foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
However, the value of share transaction at the NSE dropped
from 69 million Dollars to 63 million Dollars while market
capitalization declined from 3.3 billion Dollars at the end of
March to 3.1 billion Dollars in June.
</P>
<P>
The fall in value of share transaction and depression on the
market capitalization have been attributed to losses in share
prices which was fueled by poor corporate earnings and dim
expectations for the future, press reports said.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the NSE all-share index fell by 8.5 percent in the
first half to 5892.05 in contrast to a growth of 21 percent from
January to June last year, the NSE report said.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the all-share index, it added, was a reflection of
the "negative market response to declining corporate earnings and
the cash flow problems of investors."
</P>
<P>
On the prospect of NSE, Oladejo noted that "foreign portfolio
investors were not encouraged by the uncertainty in the political
environment and the lack of modalities for implementing the
proposed privatization program." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
