with buyers largely sidelined in a nervous environment brought on
by outbreaks of strife in emerging economies.
</P>
<P>
After Wall Street's drop on Friday, weak European markets and a
sharp fall in Japan contributed to the negative sentiment.
</P>
<P>
"We're just taking a lead from the overseas markets once again
and also the dollar was very weak which will worry the markets,"
Sam Panetta from Shaw Stockbroking said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index finished 59.3 points lower at 4596.4.
</P>
<P>
Insurance major AMP was 34 cents lower after announcing a
half-year net profit, and competitor National Mutual plummeted 19
cents as the market responded to Friday's late announcement of a
forecast sharp drop in investment earnings by its Hong Kong listed
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed 12.1 points down at 987.9 with
commodity prices broadly weaker.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was 19.5 points weaker at 964.5 as the bullion
price slipped 0.90 U.S. dollar per ounce to 283.90.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 210.84 million shares traded at a value of just
639.25 million Australian dollars (370.76 million U.S. dollars),
with falls bettering rises by 705 to 323. 
</P>
