<HEADLINE> South Pacific Forum Opens With Five PMs Absent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The annual South Pacific Forum
opened Monday in the Federated States of Micronesia (FSM) with the
prime ministers of five major members absent from the summit
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The forum is scheduled to discuss an economic action plan aimed
at helping the struggling island members ease their dependency on
aid and develop sustainable economies, the Australian Associated
Press (AAP) reported Monday from Pohnpei, Micronesia.
</P>
<P>
Australia has made clear its objection to a proposal for a
South Pacific free trade area, and is instead proposing all
nations in the region to lower tariffs in a non-discriminatory
manner.
</P>
<P>
The forum groups Australia, New Zealand, Cook Islands, FSM,
Fiji, Kiribati, Nauru, Niue, Palau, Papua New Guinea (PNG),
Marshall Islands, Samoa, Solomon Islands, Tonga, Tuvalu and
Vanuatu.
</P>
<P>
The AAP report said this year's forum was undermined by the
absence of leaders from virtually all the major members, including
Australian Prime Minister John Howard, and the prime ministers of
New Zealand, PNG, Solomon Islands and Samoa.
</P>
<P>
The absence of the leaders made many observers question the
long term future of the annual meeting of South Pacific leaders,
which is now in its 28th year.
</P>
<P>
However, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer, who is
representing Howard at this year's summit, insists that Australia
has no intention of abandoning forum members, who receive 270
million U.S. dollars of Australian aid every year. Australia is
the second largest aid provider to these members after Japan.
</P>
<P>
"They are in our backyard, and ... they are very important to
us," he said.
</P>
<P>
A joint Australia-New Zealand plan for a South Pacific whale
sanctuary, which is reportedly opposed by Japan, has angered many
smaller island members attending the meeting, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Australia Monday also unveiled an aid program to help South
Pacific governments deal with the Year 2000 computer bug problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Begins to Streamline Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean Defense Ministry
announced Monday that the Armed Forces Athletics Corps and the
Nursing Academy will be disbanded in the next few years as part of
the efforts to streamline the military.
</P>
<P>
Due to the nation's economic crisis, the ministry has pushed
for reform in the military after Kim Dae-jung was sworn in as
president last February.
</P>
<P>
The sports unit will stop enlisting athletes in October this
year and will be disbanded in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
This unit, established in 1994 and consisting of 335 athletes
and more than 400 officers, soldiers and civilian employees, won
five medals in the 1988 Seoul Summer Olympics and two in the 1992
Barcelona Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces Nurse Academy, set up 1967, will stop
recruiting new members next year. After it is closed down in
2003, the Defense Ministry plans to recruit nurses from nursing
colleges.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry also said that five military hospitals in
Pochon, Masan, Chinhae and Pohang and three other mobile Army
surgical hospitals will be deactivated in the next two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
