<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Seleznev Hold Telephone Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Monday telephoned Gennady Seleznev, speaker of the State Duma
(lower house of the parliament) on the set-up of a tripartite
conciliation commission, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The conciliation commission, to be composed of the government
now under Viktor Chernomyrdin, the State Duma and the Federation
Council, or upper house of parliament, was to develop an
anti-crisis program, Yeltsin's Spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
Yastrzhembsky said Yeltsin had authorized Chernomyrdin to
discuss the content of the program and cabinet line-up on behalf
of the executive authority.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's offer of a conciliation commission was believed to be
a gesture to seek peace with lawmakers, especially hostile
deputies of the opposition factions in the State Duma, who only
last Friday passed a resolution urging Yeltsin to step down
voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
News on Chernomyrdin's authority on personnel matters had
already emerged earlier on Monday. Some reports said that the
60-year-old Chernomyrdin had set this as a precondition for his
return to government.
</P>
<P>
About five months ago, Chernomyrdin's cabinet was dismissed by
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
As activities heat up over composition of the new cabinet,
Chernomyrdin held meetings with leaders of various factions of the
State Duma in an effort to rally support.
</P>
<P>
However, Chernomyrdin said he would only announce the roster of
the new cabinet after the State Duma approved his nomination as
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Besides meeting Chernomyrdin on Monday afternoon, Yeltsin also
held what was described as "working meetings" with the acting
defense, interior ministers, and acting head of the Federal
Security Service, the presidential press service said. 
</P>
