Victor Chernomyrdin said Monday that he will name the new
cabinet's members only when his appointment was approved by the
State Duma, or the lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the government building -- the white house
at noon, Chernomyrdin said that "as soon as I am confirmed as
prime minister by the State Duma, I will announce the composition
of the new Cabinet," the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
However, it was said that the State Duma has decided to entrust
parliamentary speaker Gennady Seleanyov to request the president
to withdraw the nomination of Chernomyrdin to the post of prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address to the nation, Yeltsin said on Monday
that the appointment of Chernomyrdin is a sign of continuity of
government ahead of the elections in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin also called on the parliament, regional leaders, and
the citizens "to understand and support" his decision to appoint
Chernomyrdin as the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin is currently holding talks with ex-Prime Minister
Sergei Kiriyenko and is expected to meet for consultations with
Grigory Yavlinsky, who leads the Yabloko faction, and Vladimir
Zhirinovsky, the leader of the Liberal Democratic faction.
</P>
<P>
The acting prime minister said that he wants "to hear
proposals of leaders of the Duma factions, including on personnel
issues." 
