<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian PM Heads for U.S. to Meet King Hussein </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's new Prime Minister Fayez
Tarawneh left here Monday morning for Washington to meet King
Hussein to report on the work schedule of his cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying Tarawneh on his U.S. trip was Jawad Anani, the new
chief of Royal Court, which is a powerful body in charge of the
royal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh, former chief of the Royal Court, took over last
Thursday the premiership from Abdul Salam Majali, who resigned to
take responsibility for the worsening economic situation and a
water pollution in the capital in July.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein has been hospitalized at the Mayo Clinic,
Rochester in Minnesota State, since July to treat the cancer in his
lymphatic tissue with chemotherapy. He ordered the government
reshuffle from his hospital bed in the U.S. last week.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the king finished his second session of
chemotherapy and went to Washington for recuperation.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh, in his first public address since the formation of
his government, said on Saturday that he and his colleagues would
do their best to restore the people's confidence in the government
by improving its administration of political, economic and
diplomatic affairs.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to ensure the transparency of government work, reform
a stagnant economy, streamline a bloated civil administration,
curb unemployment, combat poverty and develop relations with the
Arab countries and other nations.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that domestic issues, mainly the economic reform,
would top the agenda of the 23-member cabinet, which was dominated
by technocrats and leading economists.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh, himself a United States-educated economist, has
appointed several leading economists to lead the ministries of
finance, planning and development affairs.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Development Affairs Tahir Kan'an is a
development economist and former minister of planning.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Mishail Marto was former deputy governor
of the Central Bank and has played an active role in helping the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank implement their
10-year economic restructuring program in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
And Minister of Planning Nabeel Ammari, who once led the
Jordanian delegation that negotiated Jordan's entry into the
Euro-Mediterranean Partnership Agreement, has been in charge of
negotiating Jordan's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
With such an efficient team and the economic reform-oriented
agenda, Tarawneh intends to realize a 6 percent economic growth so
to curb unemployment, combat poverty and improve people's living
standard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
