<HEADLINE> Antique Furniture Repaired in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Dilapidated old furniture, most
dating back to the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-1911)
dynasties, are taking on the look of their original features after
being renovated by the Beijing Inlaid Gold Lacquer Ware Plant.
</P>
<P>
The plant has repaired more than 1,000 pieces of antique
furniture by taking advantage of a technique from the Chinese
imperial palace workshop.
</P>
<P>
The furniture are made of a variety of materials such as camphor,
cypress, elm and China fir, and includes beds, cabinets, painted
screens, cases, and tables and chairs.
</P>
<P>
Most of the pieces were useless before being repaired, paint
peeled off and falling apart.
</P>
<P>
The antique furniture were gathered from all over the country,
some of it from the remains of old houses or even discarded as
junk..
</P>
<P>
The plant collected the furniture and shipped them back to
Beijing where craftsmen do the repair work.
</P>
<P>
Antique furniture are popular on both the domestic and
international markets including the United State, Canada, Britain,
France, Germany, Belgium, Holland and Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
