<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Dredges Urban Rivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua)-- Beijing citizens soon may have
the romance of sailing on the Changhe River in the western part of
the city, just like Parisians enjoy the Seine.
</P>
<P>
This could become a reality when the dredging of the Changhe
River is completed at the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The 5.5-kilometer-long Changhe River begins at the Miyun
Reservoir Canal in the western suburbs of Beijing and flows into
the North City Moat, passing Purple Bamboo Court Park, the
Five-Pagoda Temple, the Beijing Zoo and the Beijing Exhibition
Center.
</P>
<P>
Due to sewage pollution, some parts of the river were less than
five meters wide, and the banks were overgrown and covered by
weeds and rubbish. More than 40 sewage pipes turned the river into
a putrid gutter.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, the city government invested one billion yuan
to improve the city rivers, including the Changhe River and the
Imperial Palace Moat.
</P>
<P>
The Changhe River, connecting with the Miyun Canal, will become
a 20-kilometer prime water course for sightseeing from the Summer
Palace to the Jade Abyss Pool Park, after it regains its former
purity.
</P>
<P>
The water surface then will be more than 30 meters wide,
enough for large boats carrying 30 to 50 passengers to sail along.
</P>
<P>
But the responsible authorities haven't shown much interest in
boating. The Beijing Tourism Bureau worries that the river will
be crowded by motorized boats if water-based sightseeing is
permitted.
</P>
<P>
Boating between the Summer Palace and the Jade Abyss Pool Park
began four years ago, but came to a premature end because of such
problems.
</P>
<P>
An official in charge of the city rivers and lakes said that
the noise and pollution caused by motorized boats are problems
which must first be solved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
