<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strengthens Party Leadership in Universities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The draft law has been submitted to the nation's highest
legislature for deliberation during a six-day session which opened
today.
</P>
<P>
The law was revised in response to suggestions legislators and
localities tabled during previous legislative sessions, said Qiao
Xiaoyang, vice chairman of the NPC Law Committee.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of institutions of higher education is to train
talented specialists and thus was extremely to strengthen Party
leadership," said Qiao, noting that universities successfully
carried out "the presidential responsibility system" under the
leadership of Party committees for many years.
</P>
<P>
The revision empowers Party committees in universities and
colleges to "determine operational procedure and leaders for
internal organizations, and to discuss and decide major issues
concerning the reform, development and fundamental management
system of the institutions."
</P>
<P>
Committees will also be responsible for "enforcing the
policies and guidelines of the Chinese Communist Party, ensuring
adherence to the socialist educational orientation and leading
work related to political, ideological and moral education."
</P>
<P>
University presidents are "responsible for all work related to
teaching, scientific researches and other administrative work,"
according to the draft law.
</P>
<P>
Their duties include formulating development programs,
university bylaws, developing and enforcing annual plans,
recommending candidates for various posts, including vice
presidents, hiring or firing staff, and rewarding or punishing
students.
</P>
<P>
However, the latest revision will not apply to nongovernmental
universities which have "more complicated internal management
systems," said Qiao.
</P>
<P>
He said the revision also includes a stipulation encouraging
more nongovernmental institutions of higher education to improve
programs to train the young generation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0159 </DOCNO>
