<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plummet in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo
Monday after the political uncertainty in Russia and fears of a
potential financial crisis in Latin America sent stock prices
lower around the globe last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange plunged 309.84 points, or 2.03
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 14,988.36, falling
below 15,000 for the first time in a week.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index, covering all First
Section issues, lost 18.21 points or 1.55 percent to 1,158.30.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section dropped to an estimated 310
million shares from Friday's 358.16 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan was the day's most heavily
traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Stocks fell sharply in Tokyo from the beginning of trading
following the gloom at the end of last week in major world markets
including Frankfurt, London and New York, where shares all dropped
Friday on fears over Russia's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In reaction, Tokyo investors dumped large quantities of
export-oriented shares, rattled by the prospects of lower
corporate earnings due to these overseas developments.
</P>
<P>
Traders also noted that the crisis in emerging Asian markets
seems to have spread to South American countries including Chile,
Brazil and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,334 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outnumbered gainers by 900 to 210, with 150 issues remaining
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
