<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Unified Contract Code Goes To Lawmakers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The long-awaited contract draft,
five years in the making, was finally put before China's top
lawmakers here today.
</P>
<P>
With 441 articles, compared with the three existing with 140
articles, the new law will be the country's first unified law
governing all economic agreements, according to lawmakers of the
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Hu Kangsheng, deputy director of the Legislative Affairs
Committee of the NPC Standing Committee, explained the draft to
the legislature's fourth meeting, which opened today.
</P>
<P>
According to Hu, the new law is based on the three existing
contract laws, which deal separately with domestic economic
contracts, foreign trade contracts and technology contracts, as
well as court explanations relating to contract disputes over the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
"As to the new issues surfacing in the course of the ongoing
economic reform of which China has no experience, more overseas
practices have been borrowed for this draft law," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It will be more comprehensive and detailed and easier to
enforce," he added.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the three fragmented, incomplete and sometimes even
contradictory existing contract laws, the new law covers all
debtor-creditor relationships between equal entities, but excludes
economic management activities by the government and agreements on
marriage and adoption and custody, which will be defined by other
laws.
</P>
<P>
The draft sets five principles for legally enforceable
agreements: equality, mutual willingness, fairness, honesty and
credibility, and consistency with the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
