<HEADLINE> China Intensifies Anti-flood Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The State Council, China's
cabinet, has sent a fact-finding group to Hunan Province, one of
the hardest-hit flood areas, for damage assessment and
rehabilitation preparations.
</P>
<P>
The group, headed by Zhou Yongkang, minister of Land and
Natural Resources, will focus on harnessing Dongting
Lake by giving up farmland in order to recover the lake area.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 35 medical teams have been sent to Jalaid Banner
(County) in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region to treat more
than 25,000 sick farmers and herdsmen.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the 11,000-square-kilometer Banner was
inundated, and more than 10,000 households lost their
crops and houses. The local government raised 20 million yuan to
provide its 260,000 affected people with food and other
necessities.
</P>
<P>
In Heilongjiang Province, railway workers and soldiers are
working to restore traffic to the suspended Harbin-Manzhouli
Railway, which is part of the first Eurasian Continental Bridge.
</P>
<P>
Qiqihar City along the Nenjiang River has so far used over 12
million sandbags, 21.1 tons of iron wire, and 8,642 cubic meters
of lumber to fight four flood crests.
</P>
<P>
Affected areas in Chongqing Municipality on the upper reaches
of the Yangtze River are busy rush-harvesting their ripe
crops. Flood and mud-flows in this area have claimed more than 370
lives this year and affected nearly 20 million people, resulting
in some 7 billion yuan in direct losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Unified Contract Code Goes To Lawmakers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The new law details procedures for contract signing, validity,
and enforcement, responsibility for breaking contracts, and
contract supervision.
</P>
<P>
To prevent contract-related fraud and protect the interests of
creditors, the draft empowers creditors with the right to
terminate a contract if it is discovered that the other side is
intending to cheat or is not able to discharge the terms of the
contract.
</P>
<P>
Creditors are also entitled to the subrogation right of claim
and the right to appeal to the court to cancel debtor transactions
such as free giveaways intended to avoid paying creditors, the
draft says.
</P>
<P>
Contracts shall be invalid if they are drawn up out
fraudulently, with coercion, or by taking advantage of the other
side's precarious position which go against the real intent of
that side; or if the contract conspires to violate the interests
of the state, or a third party.
</P>
<P>
"As China is shifting the majority of its economy to the
market, a unified and comprehensive contract is urgently needed,"
another official from the Legislative Affairs Committee said.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the great number of commodities and production
materials controlled by the state 20 years ago, there are now only
five such items: crude oil, oil products, petroleum, coal and
automobiles, which remain in the hands of the State Development
Planning Commission, he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that more than four billion new contracts
are registered with government industry and commerce bureaus
each year, and Chinese courts handle three million contract
disputes annually.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 430,000 Lepers Cured in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Out of the 472,000 lepers
diagnosed in China from 1949 to 1997, 430,000 have been cured, and
there were only about 6,000 lepers in the country by the end of
1997, according to one expert.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xiangsheng, who is associated with a national center for
the control of venereal diseases and leprosy under the Chinese Academy
of Medical Sciences, said here today that the prevalence rate of
leprosy in China has fallen from 2 per 10,000 people in the 1960s to
the present 0.056 per 10,000.
</P>
<P>
Leprosy, a chronic infectious disease, has a history of more
than 2,000 years in China, and was widely spread in China before
1949, according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
After New China was founded in 1949, the Chinese government paid
great attention to the prevention and treatment of the
disease, and comprehensive measures have been taken and a leprosy
examination system has been set up nationwide, said Chen.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has set strict standards to eliminate the
disease, requiring all counties and cities to keep the
prevalence rate of leprosy under 0.1 per 10,000.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 14 percent of all counties and cities have failed
to meet this requirement. Southwest China's Tibet Autonomous
Region, and Yunnan, Guizhou and Sichuan provinces have the highest
leprosy prevalence rate at present.
</P>
<P>
Chen estimated that those regions will be able to meet the
requirement by 2010.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that China should pay more attention to
the social problems caused by the disease, and make an effort to
dispel fears and discrimination toward lepers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Set Higher Adoption Standards for Foreigners (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- China is considering more
rigorous qualifications for foreigners seeking to adopt Chinese
children in order to "ensure the maximum safety and protect the
interests of adoptees," according to Civil Affairs Minister Doje
Cering.
</P>
<P>
The government is also preparing to relax restrictions on
domestic adoptions since an increasing number Chinese families
have the economic means to support more children, according to
remarks the minister made when explaining the revisions to the
1992 Adoption Law during today's meeting of China's highest
legislature.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji has affixed his signature and the draft law
has been submitted to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The draft revision stipulates that foreigners seeking to adopt
Chinese children must first be approved by the government in their
home country, and must then submit valid legal documents to
related Chinese agencies, including health records and proof they
have "no criminal record."
</P>
<P>
Adoption petitions and the aforementioned documents must be
confirmed by diplomatic agencies or authorized departments in both
countries.
</P>
<P>
Adoption procedures also require that parties involved in the
adopting sign a written agreement, register with the Chinese
government agency and have all documents authenticated by Chinese
notaries public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
