<HEADLINE> Germany to Expel 25,000 Lebanese Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Germany has decided to expel a
total of 25,000 Lebanese refugees in the coming weeks, Lebanon's
Daily Star newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
These refugees include 15,000 Lebanese citizens, 5,000
Palestinians holding Lebanese travel documents and 5,000 Lebanese
Kurds, Hussein Bekdash, president of the League of Lebanese
Emigrants in Germany told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Some 16,000 Lebanese refugees will be deported in the first
wave, and the others will be expelled later, he said.
</P>
<P>
Bekdash is on a visit here to discuss the issue with Lebanese
officials.
</P>
<P>
During Lebanon's 1975-90 civil war, more than 110,000 Lebanese
fled the country and sought shelter in Germany as refugees.
</P>
<P>
The German government has demanded all the Lebanese refugees
without residence leave Germany since Lebanon's civil war has
ended, Bekdash said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri has told
German officials that Lebanon is ready to accept all the
returning emigrants.
</P>
<P>
Germany has expressed willingness to provide aid in many
sectors to help the Lebanese government accommodate these
refugees, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Franz Rohrs, member of the German Lower Saxony parliament, is
in Beirut to see what kind of aid is needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
