<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has not sent any troops
to the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) to help the embattled
President Laurent Kabila in the fight with the Tutsi-led rebels.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by President Frederick Chiluba Sunday on
his arrival at the Lusaka International Airport from the one-day
emergency summit held in Pretoria, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to government-owned Times of Zambia published
Monday, Chiluba said no Zambian troops had been sent to DRC,
adding that all 14 members of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) represented were committed to securing a
peaceful resolution of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Zimbabwe, Angola and Zambia have sent
their troops to the DRC for a military intervention in the
country's three-week crisis in a bid to safeguard Kabila's
presidency.
</P>
<P>
The rebels who claimed earlier to have controlled one third of
the territory said Sunday that they were within 30 kilometers of
Kinshasa, the capital city with five million people.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's Home Affairs Minister Peter Machungwa said at the
weekend that the Zambian government had put in place stringent
measures to protect citizens from warring factions in its
northern neighbour.
</P>
<P>
He said Zambians had nothing to worry as the war in the DRC
was at the moment still confined to far flung areas. 
</P>
