<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power Station Design to Ignore Logging Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANZHIHUA (Sichuan), August 24 (Xinhua) -- China plans to
protect the environment by eliminating float channels for felled
timber from the design and construction of hydropower stations in
the upper reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Reservoirs constructed in the area will no longer include float
channels for logs, according to Cheng Zhihua, vice president of
the Chengdu Survey and Design Research Institute under China
National Power Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Cheng, chief designer of the Ertan Hydropower Station, the
second largest domestic project of its kind following the massive
Three Gorges Project, said the the initial design for the station
including a float channel with an annual handling capacity for 1.1
million cu.m.. of timber.
</P>
<P>
"However, construction of the proposed 800 million yuan float
channel has been suspended as part of effort to protect the
environment," said Cheng.
</P>
<P>
The Ertan station is located on the Yalong River, a major
Yangtze tributary. The denudation of virgin forests in upstream
areas over the years has led to increasing devastation, with
statistics showing that some 500,000 cu.m. of timber has been
felled on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
The research institute, the primary designer of power stations
in the upper reaches of the Yangtze, will abandon related design
practices, according to Cheng.
</P>
<P>
Experts note the serious erosion in the upper reaches of the
Yangtze has been a major factor contributing to this summer's
flooding along the river.
</P>
<P>
The State Council recently issued an emergency circular calling
for the expanded protection of primeval forests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
