<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Rebates Support Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Statistics released by the State
Administration of Taxation (SAT) show that related departments
handled export tax rebates totalling 4.3 billion yuan during July,
up 33.7 percent on the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Total export tax rebates for the first seven months hit 20.4
billion yuan, up 9.7 percent over the 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
SAT sources point out that the Asian financial crisis since
last July has a noticeable negative impact on China's exports. The
foreign trade value for the first seven months this year stood at
179.5 billion U.S. dollars, with exports for the period growing
at 6.9 percent to 103.1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The SAT indicates that China's foreign trade system will faces
serious conditions in terms of fulfilling this year's 10 percent
growth target for exports. The central government has attempted to
reverse the declining trend with three increases in tax rebate
rates so far this year, while the SAT has attempted to promote
export growth by formulating a series of measures to accelerate
the processing of tax rebates.
</P>
<P>
China's tax departments processed export tax rebates totalling
18.6 billion yuan during the first seven months, or 33.6 percent
of the annual target and substantially below the figure for the
1997 period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
