<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Road Toll Lowered in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 New Zealanders
have
been saved, and 1,000 serious injuries prevented, on the roads
since the
government introduced its hard-hitting road safety package three
years
ago.
</P>
<P>
The package, incorporating graphic television advertisements,
compulsory breath testing, and speed cameras, had proved effective
in
lowering New Zealand's road toll, said a report, which was
submitted by a
number of road safety researchers and issued by the New Zealand
Ministry
of Transport Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In the report, the researchers advocate extending the hidden
speed
camera program, introducing demerit points for speed camera
offenses and
improving open road conditions.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion, a Wellington-based newspaper, reported Monday
that the
New Zealand Government is expected to issue shortly a discussion
document
on stricter enforcement of road safety regulations. The document
would
look at introducing demerit points for speed camera offenses,
tightening
up mobile phone use in vehicles, and reducing allowable alcohol
limits.
</P>
<P>
According to New Zealand official yearbooks, road accidents
resulted
in 582 fatalities and injuries to 16,870 other people, with 3,153
seriously injured in 1995. The figures were reduced to 514 killed
and
14,796 injured, including 2,939 seriously injured, in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
