<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Cooperation on Treatment of Cardiovascular Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- China has introduced a series of
advanced technologies and equipment from the United States for the
treatment of cardiovascular diseases, which claim more lives than
any other diseases in China.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that China has more than 100,000 infants
suffering from congenital heart disease and in need of operations
every year. Over two million Chinese suffer from valvular heart
disease at present, and 150,000 to 200,000 patients need cardiac
valve replacements every year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, many coronary patients are under the threat of
death because they cannot get timely operation.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States are conducting a variety of
governmental and non-governmental technological and academic
exchanges to step up the treatment of cardiovascular diseases.
</P>
<P>
The Starr-Wood Cardiac Group, the largest cardiac surgical
organization in the northwest the United States, and
Qingdao No.2 People's Hospital in east China have jointly set up
an international cardiac technical exchange center.
</P>
<P>
The work of the center concentrates on the treatment of
coronary heart disease, congenial heart disease and valvular
disease, according to the director of the center, Wan Feng, a
nationally-known cardiac surgeon who has studied under Albert
Starr, inventor of the artificial cardiac valve in the United
States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian President Rejects PM Nominee for Fifth Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian President Nachagyn
Bagabandy on Monday rejected for the fifth time the nomination of
Davaadorj Ganbold as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the president last Saturday, the leadership of
the ruling union -- the Mongolian National Democratic Party and
Social Democratic Party -- nominated Davaadorj Ganbold for the
fifth time as prime minister, a presidential spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
However, President Bagabandy again refused to submit the
nomination to the Great Hural (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Instead, the president still proposed the nomination of
Dogsomin Ganbold, a member of the Great Hural and the Mongolian
National Democratic Party, for the post, the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Before this, the nomination of Davaadorj Ganbold, the chairman
of the Standing Committee of Economic Policy of the Great Hural,
had been rejected by President Bagabandy four times since he was
put forward by the ruling union this month.
</P>
<P>
Bagabandy believed that Davaadorj Ganbold was responsible for
the country's intensified banking crisis, which led to the fall of
the former cabinet in July.
</P>
<P>
Under Mongolia's law, the ruling party's parliamentary group
should discuss the nominees for prime minister with the president,
who in turn submits the nomination to the Great Hural for approval.
</P>
<P>
The ex-government led by Prime Minister Tsakhya Elbegdorj was
dismissed on July 24 as a result of its decision in May to merge
the state-owned Renovation Bank with the private Golomt Bank.
</P>
<P>
The decision was repealed by the Great Hural in mid August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
