<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassy in Uganda to Move For Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States Embassy in
Uganda will move out of the city center for the sake of security
following bomb attacks on U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania on
August 7.
</P>
<P>
A report carried by the East African weekly said the movement
of the embassy was revealed by a highly-placed official in
Uganda's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, but the U.S. Information
Service told Xinhua in a telephone interview Monday that it could
not confirm the move.
</P>
<P>
The move is a long-term security measure taken by the embassy
in light of fresh terrorist warnings against the United States
around the globe, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. embassy and British High Commission share the same
building on the Parliament avenue in downtown Kampala, almost the
only foreign missions located in city center. Most of the
foreign embassies in Uganda are located in three other places
known as Kololo, Nakasero and Bugolobi.
</P>
<P>
Since the bombings in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam which are
reported to have killed 263 people and injured more than 5,000
others, security around the U.S. embassy here has been tightened.
</P>
<P>
The avenue on which the embassy is located has been closed to
traffic and no parking has been allowed near the embassy.
Patrolling policemen, government soldiers as well as U.S. marines
have been guarding the place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
