<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Asia Urged to Jointly Safeguard Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim Monday called upon East Asian economies to
undertake joint action to safeguard their own interests.
</P>
<P>
These economies have perhaps been too trusting to the point of
leaving themselves too open to the machinations and manipulations
of foreign speculators, he said at the opening of a five-day ASEAN
Inter-Parliamentary Organization conference here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"When they (foreign speculators) talk of friendship and
cooperation, we believe them without reservations," he said,
adding that because East Asian economies had no hidden agenda,
they also did not suspect that "anyone else had any of their own
and we allowed them to plot and scheme behind our backs."
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is also finance minister, was of the view that East
Asian economies had been hurt because of certain excesses in a
free market system, excesses which had been overlooked amidst
these economies' desire to ensure rapid development of societies.
</P>
<P>
The East Asian economies and ASEAN countries need to have sober
and realistic assessments of the situation, taking into account
the interests of everyone, Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
He said the crisis in the region had given rise to internal
divisions within countries, as well as tensions and
misunderstandings among ASEAN members, which could only lead to
greater difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"We need to acquire strength from national unity and regional
solidarity if we are to succeed. Our present difficulties must not
be allowed to destroy what we have diligently built for decades --
a truly peaceful and prosperous Southeast Asia," Anwar said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Blaming commentators who had been quick to put the entire blame
on Asian governments for the present economic crisis, Anwar said,
"It is unfair, if not altogether unjust, simply to blame
governments of affected economies for the current crisis."
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the fundamental flaws in the global financial system
such as the unpredictability of the international capital market
and the destabilizing impact of short-term capital flows, as well
as the systemic fragility of the international monetary system
need to be remedied to avoid financial convulsions of increasing
severity.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that international financial institutions and
global hedge funds managers should adopt the same practices
imposed by international institutions on developing countries,
such as transparency and full disclosure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Sets Up Group to Handle European Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Exchange Dealers
Association of India has set up a working group to draw up
guidelines for handling the euro, the common currency of the
European Monetary Union, by Indian banks, official sources said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The group is also in the process of preparing an exhaustive
study on the implications of the euro on the Indian monetary
system.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to submit to the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) its
set of recommendations on the guidelines of euro operations by the
end of August.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations are also expected to cover different issues
pertaining to simultaneous handling of euro accounts and accounts
in other European currencies by Indian banks.
</P>
<P>
Since the euro would emerge as a strong alternative to the U.S.
dollar, RBI would like to tap all the possible hedging mechanisms
for the euro to curb speculations in the future, the same sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The other issues which are being looked into by RBI in regard
to euro operations include forward and spot dealings in the euro.
</P>
</TEXT>
