<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Foreign Exchange Reserves Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's foreign exchange
reserves, which saw a steady decline in the past few months,
showed signs of improvement this month, rising to 1.717 billion
U.S. dollars as of August 20 from 1.618 billion dollars at the end
of July.
</P>
<P>
The improvement was mainly a result of the country's prospering
garment industry and an improvement in its trade balance, a report
in The New Nation newspaper said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Despite the improvement, the reserve levels continued to remain
inadequate, considering the country's narrow export base, heavy
dependence on imports for industrial investment and production and
vulnerability to natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
After reaching a record high of 3.07 billion dollars at the end
of June 1995, the nation's foreign exchange holdings dropped to
2.037 billion dollars at the end of June 1996 and further to 1.719
billion dollars at the end of June 1997, the report quoted
officials of the country's central bank, Bangladesh Bank, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The foreign currency reserves continued to decline to 1.56
billion dollars in November 1997 before improving gradually to
1.82 billion dollars at the end of March 1998 and then falling
again to 1.74 billion dollars at the end of June this year.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign exchange reserves were short of the
appropriate level as recommended by the International Monetary
Fund, which asks a country to retain foreign currencies equivalent
to three months' import payments, as Bangladesh's monthly import
bills usually amount to 650 million dollars and its present
reserves could roughly meet only two and a half months' import
bills, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
