<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Newspapers to Offer Sharp Discounts for Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The mass-circulation Thai Rath
and business newspaper Than Setthakij are planning major discounts
to attract advertisers to offset shrinking revenue, the
English-language Bangkok Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time Thai Rath, the paper with the biggest
circulation in Thailand, has cut advertising charges by 30-50
percent, according to Bangkok Post.
</P>
<P>
Than Setthakij plans to offer 40-percent discounts on
advertising soon.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted an ad agency as saying media spending on
press advertisements plunged by 43 percent between January and May
this year, compared with the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
A Thai Rath advertising department source said the newspaper
usually offers 15-percent discounts to special clients only.
</P>
<P>
To qualify for the 50-percent discount, clients must spend more
than 2 million baht (50,000 U.S. dollars) in one month. Those who
reserve pages will face a 10-percent surcharge if the
advertisements are canceled.
</P>
<P>
Thai Rath would extend payment periods from 15 to 30 days for
those spending 3 million baht (75,000 dollars) and to 60 days for
those spending 6 million baht (150,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, total spending on newspaper
advertisements declined by 43 percent from 4.36 billion baht (109
million dollars) to 2.48 billion baht (62 million dollars), mainly
because big customers, especially vehicle and property firms,
recorded slow sales.
</P>
<P>
Ad spending by property firms fell by 63 percent from 2.04
billion baht (51 million dollars) to 764 million (19.1 million
dollars), while car advertising was down by 59 percent from 768
million baht (19.2 million dollars) to 314 million baht (7.85
million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
