<HEADLINE> Pak Foreign Exchange Reserves Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's foreign exchange
reserves were reduced to 750 million U.S. dollars on August 22
from 817 million dollars on August 11, the newspaper The Frontier
Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted official sources as saying the foreign
exchange reserves of 750 million dollars are enough to meet import
requirements of four weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government is striving hard to increase its
foreign exchange reserves to meet the import liabilities and its
foreign debt servicing, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
The government is banking on the financial assistance from
Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates, the sources said,
adding that assistance from the two countries was already in the
pipeline, but unfortunately, the U.S. missile attacks on
Afghanistan and Sudan had delayed this badly-needed assistance.
</P>
<P>
A total assistance of about 600 million dollars from the two
Muslim countries is expected.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan desperately needs 1 billion dollars ahead of the
second week of September, when the country's financial managers
expect a bailout package from the Islamic Development Bank as well
as the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
This South Asian nation has been on the verge of declaring a
moratorium on its external debt servicing commitments because of
the international economic sanctions imposed after its detonation
of nuclear devices at the end of May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
