<HEADLINE> Sharp Fall in British Exports to Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 24 (Xinhua) -- British exports to Sri Lanka
fell sharply in the first five months of this year because of the
strength of the pound and more competition from Asian countries,
the official newspaper Daily news reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
During the period, British exports to Sri Lanka dropped by 36
percent compared with the same period in 1997, but Sri Lanka's
exports to Britain were up 16 percent largely because demand for
garments in Britain remained high, British High Commissioner David
 Tatham was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
British investors have faith in the Sri Lanka's long-term
potential and there were good prospects in power generation, water
and sewage, roads and railways in the country, he told the annual
general meeting of the Sri Lanka-United kingdom Business Council
recently.
</P>
<P>
The report said Sri Lanka's Trade with Britain boomed last year
which was described as the boom year for bilateral trade between
Sri Lanka and the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Two-way trade between the two countries reached record levels
last year. Sri Lanka's exports to Britain increased by 18 percent
to 274 million British pounds while exports to Sri Lanka from
Britain were up by 42 percent to 211 million pounds compared with
1996, the report added. 
</P>
