<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Finalize State-Enterprise Reform Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The preliminary draft master
plan for the reform of Thailand's state enterprise sector will be
completed at the end of this month, the newspaper The Nation said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the plan calls for sectoral action plans in
the telecom, transport and energy industries by November.
</P>
<P>
Covered by the plan are also water, industrial, commercial
services, agricultural, social and technological sectors.
</P>
<P>
The privatization program is also intended to generate proceeds
to finance the reform of the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand, Provincial
Electricity Authority, Telephone Organization of Thailand,
Communications Authority of Thailand, Thai Airways International,
Bangkok Mass Transit Authority, State Railway of Thailand, Krung
Thai Bank, Bank for Agriculture and Cooperatives and Metropolitan
Electricity Authority are on the top-10 list of largest units to
be privatized.
</P>
<P>
The privatization program is expected to result in improved
economic efficiency, quality and choice of service, attraction of
higher value-added services, reduction in subsidies to state
enterprises, fewer loan guarantees by the government,
strengthening and deepening capital markets and new investment in
social and public services.
</P>
<P>
Under the master plan, the state will be responsible for
policy-making and regulatory supervision while having a limited
and defined role in operating activities.
</P>
<P>
In the future, the government will ensure that there is open
competition and a level playing field through effective
regulation.
</P>
<P>
New state-owned enterprise reform legislation will provide
framework legislation for regulatory systems.
</P>
<P>
Regulators will be responsible for licensing, compliance
monitoring, tariff setting, promotion and encouragement of
competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
