<HEADLINE> Police Crack Extensive Fraud Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Police in Central China's Henan
province have completed a 19-month investigation into a financial
fraud that involved 510 million yuan (US$61 million), China Daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Police have arrested four major suspects and recovered stolen
money and goods valuing 182 million yuan (US$22 million).
</P>
<P>
On January 31, 1997, the Zhengzhou branch of the Bank of China
(BOC) reported the discovery of fraud involving a senior local BOC
official and a businessman.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jianmin, deputy director of the BOC branch in Xingyang,
Henan province, was discovered colluding with Ren Chengjian,
chairman of Henan Sanren Group Company, in fraudulent activities.
</P>
<P>
The case is the worst in Henan in the past five decades and has
attracted the attention of provincial and central government
leaders, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The initial investigation showed that a large criminal
financial group headed by Ren committed fraud on 37 occasions in
the past two years, obtaining 347 million yuan (US$41.8 million)
and 1.5 million US dollars illegally.
</P>
<P>
Police traveled the length and breadth of the country and
finally arrested three key suspects at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
But Ren, the mastermind behind the activity, had fled to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
In January and February, two teams of local police flew to the
United States to continue the hunt for Ren. 
</P>
</TEXT>
