<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Who Is Insuring China's Insurance Industry? (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 24 (Xinhua) -- An enormous flash lit up the sky
when the Chinese Long March 2E Rocket carrying an Apstar-2
telecommunications satellite exploded 51 seconds after it took
off, three years ago, killing six people and injuring 23.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, Shanghai's Pacific Insurance Company (PIC) had
insured the satellite project and arranged reinsurance on the
overseas market, and in only 50 days, it paid 160 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dai Fengju, general manager of the People's Insurance
(Reinsurance) Company of China (PICC Re), spoke about the accident
today with Xinhua and explained reinsurance as simply "insuring
insurance".
</P>
<P>
He said that an individual insurer's ability to insure is
limited and even its total yearly income might not be enough to
pay off a claim for a big disaster or accident.
</P>
<P>
This is where reinsurance comes in, in alleviating risks and
stabilizing the insurance business.
</P>
<P>
The 56-year-old Dai is quite proud of his two-year-old company,
China's sole reinsurer, whose incomes from premiums in 1997 was
10.54 billion yuan, meaning that they are one of the world's top
20 reinsurance companies.
</P>
<P>
PICC Re is only two years old, but was honored as "Company
Launch of the Year 1997" by the magazine 'International
Reinsurance Review' for their reputation last year, Dai
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
