<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Collapsing Pagodas in Myanmar Under Renovation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 280 collapsing ancient
Buddhist pagodas, temples and buildings in Myanmar's northwestern
Bagan area, 680 kilometers from Yangon, are being renovated under
the aegis of the government.
</P>
<P>
These religious pagodas are rich with historical and cultural
heritage, drawing attention of world tourists.
</P>
<P>
A total of 890 old pagoda sites are also being excavated and
will be rebuilt with original style and taste of the 11th century,
according to Myanmar Culture Ministry sources.
</P>
<P>
Bagan, known as a land with thousands of pagodas, was hit by a
major earthquake in 1975, causing damage to pagodas and stupas
which were later renovated with the assistance of the U.N.
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is a Buddhist country with 85 percent of its population
believing in Buddhism. For nearly 1,000 years, Myanmar has kept
Theravada (Little Vehicle) Buddhism pure and intact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
