<HEADLINE> Thai Government Accused of Ignoring the Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Assembly of the Poor in
Thailand denounced the government for focusing only on financial
sector problems and ignoring the plight of the poor.
</P>
<P>
In a statement available Monday, the umbrella organization of
activists, mostly from northeastern provinces, said it would stop
negotiations with the government until the administration came up
with clear-cut measures for solving the poor's problems.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the government had focused only on solving
financial sector problems and on helping the rich, but had ignored
the plight of the poor.
</P>
<P>
The assembly annually organizes rallies at the Government House
and in major northeastern provinces to press the government to
address their problems.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the assembly would invoke the new
constitution to sponsor their own bill, which would seek to
establish an office to guarantee the poor's welfare.
</P>
<P>
The new constitution allows groups of at least 150,000 eligible
voters to submit bills to the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the assembly would gather the necessary
signatures and submit a bill to Parliament President Wan Mohammad
Noor Matha on October 11, which is the first anniversary of the
implementation of the new constitution.
</P>
<P>
"From now on we will launch every possible means to pressure
the current and future governments to issue concrete measures to
solve the poor's problems," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
