<HEADLINE> Chinese Cooperation With U.S. Aircraft Manufacturers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Aviation Industry
Corp. is planning more cooperation with the U.S's Boeing Aircraft
Co. to produce more complicated aircraft and to refit some
McDonnell Douglas planes.
</P>
<P>
The company has got more experience in the past two decades and
cooperation has gone well since McDonnell Douglas merged with
Boeing, according to Li Wanxin, general manager of the corporation.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai-based company cooperated with McDonnell Douglas in
assembling MD-82s in 1985, and since that time, has assembled 35
MDs and manufactured 3,500 parts. It is now producing tail
sections for Boeing 737-700 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The company also plans to assemble MD-90s in accordance with an
agreement signed by China Aviation Industry Corp. and McDonnell
Douglas in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Twenty MD-90s are to be assembled in Shanghai before 2000 by
the Shanghai company in cooperation with aircraft manufacturers in
the cities of Xi'an, Shenyang and Chengdu.
</P>
<P>
The first new type of passenger plane will be completed by
November of this year, Li says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
