<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Slashes Economic Growth Goal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
decided to slash the country's gross national product (GNP) growth
rate to 2 percent from the early-projected 3 percent, a newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In its revised economic growth targets for this year, the
government is forecasting a maximum 2-percent GNP growth by
yearend after insisting on a 3-percent goal early this year,
according to Business World.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of the gross domestic product (GDP) has similarly
been downscaled to 1.5 percent from a previous 2.4-percent
projection.
</P>
<P>
These adjustments were made by the interagency Development
Budget Coordinating Committee after the resident representative of
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to the Philippines predicted
earlier a 1-percent GNP growth rate for the country in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The GNP represents a country's total output of goods and
services including income from abroad while GDP represents only
domestic production.
</P>
<P>
The new growth targets, along with projections for 1999, will
be presented to the congress Monday when deliberations on the
proposed 579.5 billion peso 1999 budget begin.
</P>
<P>
The government also lowered its economic targets for 1999, with
the GNP growth rate revised to 4 percent from an original 5
percent. The GDP is expected to grow 3.5 percent, a full
one-percentage-point lower than the original prediction of 4.5
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
