</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Foreign Loans Decline Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Foreign loans listed with the
Central Bank of the Philippines fell by 45 percent in the first
seven months this year to 3.4 billion U.S. dollars from 6.2
billion dollars a year ago, according to the central bank.
</P>
<P>
In a report published here Monday, Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson attributed the decline to relatively high interest
rates prevalent in the market up to the present and to the falling
value of the Philippine peso which continues to be under
speculative attack.
</P>
<P>
"The widening spreads on Philippine debt coupled with the
depreciation of the peso have particularly discouraged private
companies from tapping the international capital market for
funds," Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign loans must be first registered with the central bank so
that these may be eligible for dollar servicing later via the
Philippine Dealing System, the country's electronic foreign
exchange market.
</P>
<P>
Those that have not been cleared first by the central bank will
have to source their dollars elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the country's current foreign reserves
are estimated at around 10.6 billion dollars or roughly equal to
2.3 months worth of imports or foreign obligations.
</P>
<P>
Foreign borrowings by the country's private sector for the
first seven months in 1998 dropped by 72 percent to 1.2 billion
dollars from 4.1 billion dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The public sector's foreign borrowings, however, increased 9
percent to 2.2 billion dollars during the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
