<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BJP Calls for Better Coordination Among Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP) Sunday called for better coordination and greater
cooperation among the coalition partners, according to the Press
Trust of India (PTI).
</P>
<P>
Apparently ignoring the threat of withdrawal of support for the
BJP-led government by All-India Anna Dravida Muunetra Kazhagam
(AIADMK), a political resolution adopted Sunday at the end of a
three-day meeting of the BJP National Executive chose to
concentrate attack on the opposition particularly the Congress.
</P>
<P>
AIADMK, based in the southern state of Tamil Nadu and a
decisive partner of the BJP in the coalition government, has
threatened several times to withdraw its support since the BJP
came to power last March.
</P>
<P>
Without even mentioning the name of AIADMK, the resolution
merely said the government has to work within the limitations of
coalition politics in light of experiences of the last five
months, PTI reported from Jaipur, capital city of the northwestern
State of Rajasthan.
</P>
<P>
Accusing the opposition parties of ganging up to try and
subvert the BJP-led government, the ruling party called on the
people to rebuff these disruptive forces and ensure that the
polity was not destabilized.
</P>
<P>
The decision-making body of the BJP adopted a resolution
Saturday asserting that India had the strength and capacity to
withstand and survive the economic sanctions imposed by many
countries and international organizations following the country's
nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
The National Executive favored reviewing a decision of the
BJP-led government on a nuclear moratorium if future developments
jeopardized India's national strategic and security interests.
</P>
<P>
The executives asked the government not to sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT), saying it is
"discriminatory."
</P>
<P>
Members of the executive were critical of the failure of the
coalition government to curb mounting prices in the country since
the nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
An economic resolution adopted Sunday by the executives blamed
the price rise on previous governments and unfavorable weather
conditions.
</P>
<P>
PTI quoted party sources as saying the BJP-led coalition came
in for sharp criticism by some members at the meeting for its
failure to ease the price rise which, they felt, was eroding the
vote banks of the BJP.
</P>
<P>
The BJP elite suggested that the public distribution system be
streamlined and strengthened and distribution of essential
commodities at reasonable rates be ensured so that the common
people are relieved of the burden of back-breaking prices and
shortages created by hoarders.
</P>
<P>
The prices of essential commodities have skyrocketed since the
BJP-led government came to power last March and especially since
the country conducted nuclear tests in May, with some having
increased by more than 10 times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
