<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- Australian Prime Minister John Howard and opposition leader
Kim Beazley sharpened the decision facing voters at the coming
federal poll Sunday to choose between the Howard government's big
goods and services tax-based shakeup of the tax system and the
opposition party's more cautious tax reform plan.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian Foreign Affairs and Trade Department has
systematically concealed for nearly 23 years its detailed
foreknowledge of the Indonesian attack at Balibo in East Timor in
which five Australia-based journalists were killed.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- Thousands of senior citizens in Victoria state, southern
Australia, are living in nursing homes that fail to meet the most
basic standards of care.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- Facing losses running into billions of dollars, western
banks and financial investment funds will know Monday what the
forced 40 billion U.S. dollar restructuring of Russia's short-term
debt market will cost them. 
</P>
