<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Salary Grievance Hearing to Determine Leverage in Lockout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The NBA and the Players
Association resume their legal wrangling Monday as an arbitrator
begins a hearing to determine whether player contracts are
guaranteed despite the lockout and which side will have
bargaining leverage in future negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Arbitrator John Feerick will hear two days of testimony before
making what is expected to be a quick ruling on the grievance
filed by the union, which calls for players to be paid during the
lockout. The NBA, which unsuccessfully tried to remove Feerick
as arbitrator, contends its actions are entirely legal during a
work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
Feerick's ruling will have a major effect on future collective
bargaining sessions, which have digressed from unproductive to
acrimonious over the the last four months and are threatening the
start of the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
The NBA is the only major pro sports league that never has
lost a game to a work stoppage.
</P>
<P>
Feerick upheld the sanctity of the guaranteed contract in the
case of Latrell Sprewell, whom he reinstated as a member of the
Golden State Warriors after the team terminated his 25 million
U.S. dollars contract.
</P>
<P>
The grievance was filed on behalf of some 220 players just
hours before NBA owners imposed the lockout. And the lockout a
llowed Feerick to remain as arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
Eleven players were named in the grievance the union filed on
behalf of more than 200 players whose pay schedules would be
affected by a lockout. They includes Boston Celtics guard Kenny
Anderson, who was to receive his entire 5.8 million salary for
next season on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Other players are scheduled to receive similar payments this
summer, but the NBA maintained it is under no obligation to pay
the salaries. In March, Feerick shortened the NBA's one-year
suspension and reinstated the contract of Sprewell, the All-Star
guard who attacked coach in a practice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
