<HEADLINE> Kucera Wins Pilot Pen Tennis Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Karol Kucera of Slovakia
ended Goran Ivanisevic's hopes for his first American title
Sunday, beating the eighth seeded Croatian in three sets to win
the 870,000 U.S. dollars Pilot Pen international tennis event in
New Haven, Connecticut, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Ivanisevic has won 21 career singles titles but is now winless
in five finals on American soil. He complained of bad calls and
a sore left shoulder but ultimately was undone by Kucera's smooth
all-court game.
</P>
<P>
"In the beginning it was hurting," Ivanisevic said of the
shoulder that caused him problems in his semifinal win over
Yevgeny Kafelnikov of Russia. "Not on the first serve, but on the
second serve. That is why I started to hit some different second
serves."
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed Kucera earned 122,500 U.S. dollars and captured
his second title of the year in one hour 45 minutes as he beat
Ivanisevic for the third stragiht time in four meetings. He won
the Sydney International in January and was a finalist at the Me
rcedes Cup claycourt event in Stuttgart, Germany last month.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Kucera will jump back into the top 10 when the
ATP rankings are released Monday. The Slovak was ranked a
career-high No. 9 earlier this season. The U.S. Open seeding
committee likely will use those rankings as its basis seeding at
the final Grand Slam of the year in eight days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
