<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Sacks Government, Reinstates Chernomyrdin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
on Sunday sacked the whole cabinet of Sergei Kiriyenko and named
ex-premier Viktor Chernomyrdin as interim Prime Minister.
</P>
<P>
The move marks another surprise turn in Russia's unpredictable
political climate. Chernomyrdin himself was fired just about five
months ago together with most of his cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year-old Kiriyenko, barely four months since he took
office, left the Government House Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko's ouster came one week after the government and the
central bank raised the ceiling of the ruble's exchange corridor
from 6.3 to 9.5 rubles to the U.S. dollar, which amounted to a
devaluation of the national currency.
</P>
<P>
A 90-day moratorium was also imposed on repayments of foreign
debts.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Kiriyenko cabinet was already facing an angry
State Duma, or lower house of parliament, where Communists were
threatening a vote of non-confidence and most law-makers expressed
dissatisfaction over the government's handling of the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
As Russia's stock market plunged to record lows amid an ever
weaker ruble, the economic prospect looked as bleak as ever, if
not worse.
</P>
<P>
Prices of the most liquid shares on the Russian market shed an
alarming 25-40 percent over the past week alone amid extremely
thin trading.
</P>
<P>
Observers had expected the stock market to recover somewhat
next Monday when the government, now the ex-government, was
scheduled to announce details of a planned swap of short-term
government treasury bills into longer-term securities, another
step announced last Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Russians' average real income, or after-tax income adjusted
for inflation, dropped 8.9 percent in the first seven months of
the year as compared with the same period of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The latest government shake-up received mixed reaction from the
Russian political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
Duma Speaker Gennady Seleznyov welcomed news of Kiriyenko's
demise, saying it was expected as the Kiriyenko team "is not
capable of working efficiently," Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
However, he blasted Yeltsin's choice of Chernomyrdin as the
interim premier.
</P>
<P>
"This endeavor is unlikely to succeed since Kiriyenko's
government... continued what the former Cabinet was doing,"
Seleznyov said.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Shokhin, leader of the Our Home is Russia (NDR)
faction in the Duma, hailed the comeback of Chernomyrdin, who is
chairman of the NDR movement.
</P>
<P>
He said Yeltsin sorted things out after returning from vacation
and that Kiriyenko, central bank governor Sergei Dubinin and
Yeltsin's chief negotiator with international lending agencies
Anatoly Chubais had failed to reveal the actual situation in full
to Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov, who had never recognized the
cabinet of Kiriyenko, blasted Yeltsin's move as "an upside down
decision" based on willpower without consulting parliament.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko was picked from the obscurity of a minor position in
the energy ministry to replace Chernomyrdin in March, less than
one year in the Kremlin politics.
</P>
<P>
Over its brief life, the Kiriyenko cabinet had for the most
part played the role of fire-fighters, as the country was rocked
by railway blockades staged by miners who were not paid for months
and waves of financial crises, dashing Yeltsin's ambition of "a
year of growth" this year.
</P>
<P>
The government's efforts to prop up the ruble and boost the
stock markets, even with over 22 billion U.S. dollars of loans
pledged from Western lenders, succumbed to waning investor
confidences.
</P>
<P>
Last Monday's move by the Kiriyenko government to effectively
devalue the national currency was seen as a step that erased one
of the few economic achievements of Yeltsin's presidency, a stable
ruble exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, who is already reportedly making political
consultations on possible line-up of a new cabinet, is expected to
return to the Government House Monday.
</P>
<P>
If he was to serve as prime minister for an extended period of
time, confirmation would have to be sought from the State Duma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> League of Arab States Supporting Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- The Secretariat of the
Arab States condemns the U.S. bombing of a Pharmaceutical factory
near Khartoum in Sudan on Friday, according to a document issued
by the U.N. spokesman's office on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The condemnations were contained in a letter to the president of
the U.N. Security Council from the Charge d'affaires a.i. of
Kuwait's Permanent Mission to the U.N., who is August Chairman of
the Arab Group and speaks on behalf of the 22-member League of
Arab States (LAS).
</P>
<P>
The LAS Secretariat "considers this unjustified act a blatant
violation against the sovereignty of the LAS, and against its
national territorial integrity as well as against all of
international laws and tradition, particularly the Charter of the
U.N.," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
The Secretariat calls upon the U.S. to respect international
legitimacy and "refrain from such acts which constitute violations
of national sovereignty, instigating feelings of popular outrage,
encouraging violence and counter-violence, thus endangering
international peace and security," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
The letter said the Arab Group supports Sudan in its request
for the Security Council to consider the U.S. attacks and send a
fact-finding mission to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
U.S. launched missile attacks on "terrorist targets" in
Afghanistan and Sudan on Friday in response to terrorist bombings
in Kenya and Tanzania on August 7.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
