<HEADLINE> Khatami Vows to Fight Terrorists After Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami on Sunday vowed to fight terrorists, hours after the
former chief prosecutor, Assadollah Lajevardi was assassinated by
two gunmen.
</P>
<P>
"The government is determined to do everything possible within
its capacity against notorious terrorists," Khatami said in a
message of condolence to the supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei
and the family of Lajevardi.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA quoted Khatami as urging
information and security organs to quickly identify and arrest the
terrorists who gunned down Lajevardi and two other people.
</P>
<P>
Lajevardi, along with his brother and a passer-by were killed
in an assassination by two armed assailants at his business office
in Tehran's grand bazaar, a traditional marketplace.
</P>
<P>
One of the assailants was arrested and police cordoned off the
bazaar shortly after the attack. It was reported that the
foreign-based opposition Mujahedin Khalq claimed responsibility
for the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Mujahedin accused Lajevardi of being responsible for the
notorious killing and arrest of tens of thousands of dissidents in
the early years of the Islamic revolution since 1979.
</P>
<P>
Lajevardi, who was a confidant of the late supreme leader
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, had "a bright record of services" for
the Islamic revolution, IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
Once a prisoner in the late shah's regime, Lajevardi was asked
to administer the Prisons Organization after establishment of the
Islamic Republic of Iran in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Former President Hashemi Rafsanjani and Majlis (Parliament)
Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq Nouri also issued separate messages
condemning the terrorist murder.
</P>
<P>
Lajevardi supported Nouri in last year's presidential election,
which the speaker lost to Khatami. He resigned last year and
returned to the same business he did in the bazaar before the
revolution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
