<HEADLINE> Egypt, Syria Narrows Gap on Peace Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said Sunday that Egypt and Syria will soon reach an
understanding on an Egypt's proposal to convene an international
conference to revive the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon his return from a surprise visit to
Damascus, Moussa said he will report to President Hosni Mubarak
the results of his "lengthy talks" with Syrian President Hafez
Assad and Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides are still coordinating their stances on
the issue, but "the time will come soon to reach an understanding
on this subject."
</P>
<P>
Amid efforts to seek ways to break the 16-month-old deadlock in
the Palestinian-Israeli talks, France and Egypt put forth an
initiative in May for an international conference on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Syria has reservations over holding the conference, fearing
that it could give Israel a pretext to wriggle out of the
principles of the 1991 Madrid Conference, which lay the basis for
the process.
</P>
<P>
Syria broken off peace talks with Israel in early 1996 and
vowed not to resume the negotiations unless Israel agreed to pull
back from the Golan Heights, which it captured in the 1967 Mideast
war and annexed in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said he delivered a message from Mubarak to Assad and
received a reply. But he did not disclose the content of either
message.
</P>
<P>
He said his visit to Damascus was part of the continued
consultations between the two countries on the peace process and
the general situation in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Moussa denied reports that his visit was to arrange for an
visit by Mubarak to Damascus.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Mubarak and Assad exchange visits periodically
and "this takes place in the normal manner." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
