<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-23 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Files Claim for Compensation From U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Sudan requested that the United
States compensate for the damages of el-Shifa pharmaceutical
plant, attacked by the U.S. Thursday under the pretext that it was
producing chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese News Agency reported that about 300 workers of the
plant made the claim for compensation from the U.S. for the losses
they suffered, including the loss of their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of the plant Sayed Haj Hamad put the damages
of the plant at 100 million U.S. dollars - the value of the
facilities, equipment, pharmaceuticals and other materials in the
plant.
</P>
<P>
Sudan insisted the plant was producing medicines for human and
veterinary consumption and export some of the drugs to finance the
import of other medicines.
</P>
<P>
The plant was one of the largest in Africa and used to produce
20 kinds of human medicines and 23 kinds of veterinary ones. Its
production went to some Arab and African countries beside meeting
domestic demands.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese officials pointed out that the lack of such medicines
will give rise to medicine price hikes and affect the growth of
the animal wealth in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Sudanese Association for Patient Protection
asked for an immediate apology from the United States for its
fatal mistake and urged the U.S. to rebuild the plant and offer
real compensations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. fired cruise missiles on the pharmaceutical plant in
the industrial zone in north Khartoum under the claim that it
produced the deadly VX nerve gas.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government dismissed the accusation and cited Tom
Carnavin, a British engineer who took part in the construction of
the plant, as saying that the plant "could never produce the nerve
gas VX." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
