<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2030 GMT, August 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman said Sunday that
the Middle East peace process must continue despite the killing of
Rabbi Shlomo Raanan, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Weizman said this while in a condolence call at Raanan's
family. The 63-year-old rabbi was stabbed to death in his home
Thursday night by a Palestinian intruder in Tel Rumeida, Hebron.
</P>
<P>
"For my whole life I have fought for the security and benefit of
Israel and no body can expressed his doubt about that," Weizman
said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his sorrow for the killing of the rabbi, but said
that Israel could live in complete peace only after reaching an
peace agreement with the Palestinians. (Israel-Weizman)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Chairman of the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) Yasser Arafat will fly to Oslo Monday to attend the fifth
anniversary celebrations of the Oslo agreements, Voice of
Palestine said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Speaker of the Palestinian Legislative Council Abu Ala and
PNA Minister of State Hasan Asfour will accompany Arafat to the
celebrations, which will be held at the Nobel Institute for Peace
in Oslo, Norway.
</P>
<P>
The Oslo agreements signed five years ago in Oslo laid down the
framework for a political solution of the Palestinian issue with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu refused to
attend the ceremonies in Oslo, saying he does not have time
because of things he has to take care of in Israel.
(Israel-Palestine-Oslo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Organization of the Islamic Conference
(OIC) said it was deeply concerned over the U.S. missile attacks
on targets in Afghanistan and Sudan, which left human casualties
and material losses.
</P>
<P>
OIC Secretary General Ezzedine Laraki said on Sunday the
Jeddah-based organization reiterates its condemnation of all forms
of terrorism but rejects any unilateral action "apart from the
international legitimacy." (OIC-US-Strikes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein on Sunday received
visiting Indian Parliament Speaker Sheri Balalogi, and discussed
with him regional and international issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency (INA) said that during the meeting,
Balalogi praised the firm bilateral relations between Iraq and
India, and expressed India's deep concern over the continuation of
sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Balalogi said the Indian government and people would support
the Iraqi people in their legitimate demands for lifting of the
sanctions, and India would work for this end. (Iraq-India)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami on Sunday vowed
to fight terrorists, hours after the former chief prosecutor,
Assadollah Lajevardi, was assassinated by two gunmen.
</P>
<P>
"The government is determined to do everything possible within
its capacity against notorious terrorists," Khatami said in a
message of condolence to the supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei
and the family of Lajevardi.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA quoted Khatami as urging
information and security organs to quickly identify and arrest the
terrorists who gunned down Lajevardi and two other people.
(Iran-Assassination) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
