<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2030 GMT, August 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli President Ezer Weizman said Sunday that
the Middle East peace process must continue despite the killing of
Rabbi Shlomo Raanan, Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
Weizman said this while in a condolence call at Raanan's
family. The 63-year-old rabbi was stabbed to death in his home
Thursday night by a Palestinian intruder in Tel Rumeida, Hebron.
</P>
<P>
"For my whole life I have fought for the security and benefit of
Israel and no body can expressed his doubt about that," Weizman
said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his sorrow for the killing of the rabbi, but said
that Israel could live in complete peace only after reaching an
peace agreement with the Palestinians. (Israel-Weizman)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Chairman of the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) Yasser Arafat will fly to Oslo Monday to attend the fifth
anniversary celebrations of the Oslo agreements, Voice of
Palestine said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Speaker of the Palestinian Legislative Council Abu Ala and
PNA Minister of State Hasan Asfour will accompany Arafat to the
celebrations, which will be held at the Nobel Institute for Peace
in Oslo, Norway.
</P>
<P>
The Oslo agreements signed five years ago in Oslo laid down the
framework for a political solution of the Palestinian issue with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu refused to
attend the ceremonies in Oslo, saying he does not have time
because of things he has to take care of in Israel.
(Israel-Palestine-Oslo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Organization of the Islamic Conference
(OIC) said it was deeply concerned over the U.S. missile attacks
