<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Porfile: Kiriyenko Sacked By President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Kiriyenko and his entire Cabinet was fired by President Boris
Yeltsin on Sunday. It was the second time the president dismissed
the Russian government within five months.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin took the decision doubtlessly because of a financial
crisis which has deepened under Kiriyenko and provoked fierce
attacks on the prime minister and the president in parliament on
Friday. The chamber demanded Yeltsin resign.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko, 36, was appointed prime minister by Yeltsin after
dismissal of the cabinet led by Chernomirdin on March 23.
</P>
<P>
When nominating Kiriyenko to the post of prime minister, the
president said that Kiriyenko as an independent politician was
skillful in keeping contacts with different parties, and that
ability and energy do not depend on ones age.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko became a millionaire through the system known as
arbitrage. Then he went into banking in Nizhny Novgorod (Gorky)
and quickly made fortune.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko had been less than a year in the Kremlin politics
when Yeltsin picked him from the obscurity of a minor position in
the energy ministry to replace the even more wealthy and
experienced Viktor Chernomirdin.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko became the first deputy minister of the fuel and
energy ministry on March 23, 1997, and then the minister in
November of that year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajikistan Expels Four Pakistanis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Four Pakistani nationals were
ordered to leave Tajikistan for spreading ideas of Islamic
fundamentalism amongst Dushabe residents, a ranking Tajik official
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tajik Deputy Security Minister Shamsullo Dzhabirov said the
four, identified as Malik Haiyat, Talhi Mohammad, Omar Mohammad
and Fahriddin Rizoyaddin, were told to leave within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
Dzhabirov said they were detained Thursday and Friday while
"being engaged in propaganda for Wahhabi ideas and distributing
illegal printings."
</P>
<P>
Wahhabi is a radical Islamic sect that is active in Central
Asia and Russia's Caucasus region.
</P>
<P>
He said the Pakistani embassy in Dushanbe, the Tajik capital,
had been notified of the investigation into the four's activities.
</P>
<P>
The four "exporters of the fundamentalist ideas and advocates
of the ideas of the Taliban" were told about the inadmissibility
of such conduct on territory of a foreign sovereign country, the
minister said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defense Minister: UK Has Evidence of Laden' Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 23 (Xinhua) - Britain claimed on Sunday to have
independent evidence that Saudi exile Osama Bin Laden was
involved in the East Africa bombings and was planning more
attacks.
</P>
<P>
"We had independent evidence to link Bin Laden with
atrocities, not only in the East African embassies but
elsewhere," British defense minister George Robertson told Sky
television.
</P>
<P>
"And we had indications that he was going to be involved in
further atrocities," Reuters quoted Robertson as saying. He did not
say where these had been expected to take place but said the targets
were "other installations in other parts of the world".
</P>
<P>
The United States launched missile attacks on Thursday
against what it said were "terrorist" targets in Afghanistan and
Sudan following the August 7 bombings of the U.S. embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Britain has expressed strong support for the U.S. missile
strikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
