<HEADLINE> Greece, Austria Favor Political Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Greece and Austria agreed Sunday
that more observers should be sent to the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo in order to find a political solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference in the northern Greek city
of Thessaloniki with Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima, Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis said that Both countries were concerned
about the developments in Kosovo because if the continuation was
negative, this would have repercussions on the entire region.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the situation in Kosovo had reached the point
that special care was required by third countries, and Greece and
Austria agreed that more observers should be sent to strife-torn
Kosovo, their safety should be ensured, so that they might exert
pressure for peaceful conditions.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Klima, whose country is currently holding the
European Union's rotating presidency, said that the alliance and
its president, namely Austria, would call on Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to stop the violence in Kosovo where ethnic
Albanians make up 90 percent of its nearly two million population.
</P>
<P>
Klima arrived Friday in Greece for a three-day private visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
