<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Urges Austria to Begin Cyprus'EU Entry Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 23 (Xinhua) -- Greece Sunday called on Austria
to begin entry talks for Cyprus into the European Union (EU) as
early as possible.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with Austrian Chancellor
Viktor Klima, who arrived Friday in Greece for a three-day private
visit, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis said that negotiations
for EU applicants including Cyprus should begin before the end of
a screening process that involves collecting data on the workings
of each country, the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Greece's position on entry talks was that talks should begin
simultaneously for the six applicants, but not necessarily on the
same subjects, he said.
</P>
<P>
Klima, whos country is currently holding the EU rotating
presidency, said that screening for EU applicants, due to end in
October or November, should be completed as soon as possible as
the outcome would have major repercussions on security, combating
organized crime, and overall progress in Europe.
</P>
<P>
But at the same time, he stressed that the EU should not allow
its interest to diminish in the five countries slated for the
second wave of entry along with Cyprus, and care should be taken
to close ties with them in order to avoid discriminatory
treatment.
</P>
<P>
Klima said that entry talks would be conducted with each of the
six countries separately, and would focus on the extent to which
each individual applicant met EU standards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980824.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton to Visit Russia as Scheduled Despite Shakeup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will go ahead with his trip to Russia scheduled at end of the
month despite Sunday's shakeup in the Russian government, said
White House spokesman P.J. Crowley on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The United States' priority is that necessary economic reforms
move forward in Russia, said Crowley, who is with the president in
Martha's Vineyard, Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
"Those policies are not specifically based on personality," he
said. "We'll continue to work closely with the Russian government
and watch the situation closely as it evolves."
</P>
<P>
Clinton is vacationing on Martha's Vineyard until August 30. He
leaves August 31 for two days of summit meetings with Yeltsin and
members of the Russian parliament in Moscow
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin dismissed Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko and the rest
of his government in a surprise announcement Sunday. He said
Sunday he was reappointing former Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin who was fired by Yeltsin in March.
</P>
<P>
Crowley said the U.S. hopes Chernomyrdin's first order on his
return will be to work closely with the federal assembly,
international financial institutions, leading sectors within the
Russian economy and private investors, and others to improve the
economic situation in Russia and restore investor confidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
